@REM==============================================================================

@node "FastInstall" "Fast Installation"

                             @{b}FAME Fast Installation
                            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

For fast installation start the installer script by double clicking
on its icon. Answer all questions about the installation.

After the installer has finished, start the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} and set some
personal settings, but you mustn't.

Now start the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} and click on Node0 to see and use the node.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Installation" "How to install FAME manually""

                          @{b}FAME Installation Procedure
                         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

To install FAME by hand, follow the steps described below:

 @{b}1.@{ub} Create a directory where you want to have FAME installed. Please make
    sure that you have at least @{fg fill}5MB@{fg text} free on the device you want to have FAME
    installed. Extract the archive '@{fg fill}FAME_MAIN.LHA@{fg text}' into your created dir and
    copy the files from the @{b}S@{ub}, @{b}L@{ub} and @{b}LIBS@{ub} drawers to your System-Directories
    @{b}S:@{ub}, @{b}L:@{ub} and @{b}LIBS:@{ub}. Also copy the contents of the @{fg fill}Bin/@{fg text} drawer to your
    FAME:Modules/ drawer.

 @{b}2.@{ub} FAME requires an Assign called @{fg fill}FAME:@{fg text} to work. You have to possibilites
    to create this assign. You could write the following line to your
    user-startup file:
                         Assign FAME: <FAME_PATH>

    Or you use the Autoassign feature of FAME. This means that the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} of
    FAME is able to create the required assign when starting the @{"Server" link "InternModules"}. To
    let this work, you must enter two tooltypes to the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} icon:

                          BBSLOCATION=<FAME_PATH>

    You @{b}MUST@{ub} enter a complete path here, i.e. DH1:FAME/ or similiar, because
    the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} creates from this path the FAME: assign, and therefore this
    has to be a full valid AmigaDOS-Path. Also the following tooltype must
    be set to use the AutoAssign feature:

                                AUTOASSIGN

    This forces the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} to create the assign before starting FAME. It's
    your choice which of the two methods you wish to use.

 @{b}3.@{ub} Check out if you have started the @{fg fill}FIFO:@{fg text} device. If you haven't used it
    until now, please add the following line to your S:User-Startup file:

                      run >NIL: <NIL: L:Fifo-Handler

 @{b}4.@{ub} Now you have to decide if you want to run some parts of FAME resident.
    Currently the @{fg fill}MainPart@{fg text}, @{fg fill}FAMEHydra@{fg text} and @{fg fill}FAMEFileChecker@{fg text} supports the
    resident feature. To use it, write down the following lines to your
    @{fg fill}FAME:SETTINGS/FAMESTART.BAT@{fg text} file:

           RESIDENT FAME:Modules/MainPart PURE
           RESIDENT FAME:Modules/FAMEFileChecker.FIM PURE
           RESIDENT FAME:Doors/FAME/FAMEHYDRA/FAMEHYDRA.FIM PURE

    Of course add only the lines of the programs you want to have resident,
    all other lines shouldn't be written. If you use the resident feature,
    please note that you @{b}MUST@{ub} remove the whole pathname of the programs you
    want to have resident, i.e. you load @{"MainPart" link "InternModules"} resident, than you have
    to remove the Path to @{"MainPart" link "InternModules"} in SystemEditor/Node Settings/MainPart.
    Only the filename should be kept so the WB is able to recognize that
    first the Resident list should be scanned before loading the program
    from HD.

 @{b}5.@{ub} After copying the files, start the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} of FAME (FAME:Modules).
    It will now create all missing files to use FAME. You must enter some
    personal settings under System Datas. After saving, you may start the
    @{"Server" link "InternModules"} to take a look to the working FAME system.

 @{b}6.@{ub} You may also install the following FAME-Only (FIM) doors, which are
    part of the FAME-Release:

     ByteKiller V3.0 by ByteAndi/tRSi - Door to delete Uploaded files
     NewFiles V0.? by ByteAndi/tRSi   - Door to view the BBS filelists
     dRE!jOIN V1.2 by dR.dRE!/tRSi    - Door to change the current conf
     dRE!wEEK V1.1 by dR.dRE!/tRSi    - Creates Top Uploader statistics
     pAGE-mASTER V0.84 by SieGeL/tRSi - Multi-Function Pager-Door

   These doors could be found in the @{fg fill}archives/@{fg text} drawer of the FAME-Release.
   We have also included some already released Doors, which run perfectly
   on FAME. These doors could be found in the @{fg fill}Goodies/@{fg text} drawer. These doors
   are ALL @{u}unregistered@{uu} Versions; to get the latest versions you have to
   register for the appropriate coder !

             @{i}That's all for installation, now start the @{"Server" link "InternModules"}
                      and enjoy your new FAME System!@{ui}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "DoorInstall" "How to built in Doors into FAME"

                        @{b}How to Add/Install Doors to FAME
                       ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

This chapter explains how to built in new doors, as example we show you how
to build in the pAGE-mASTER, which is a FIM-only door.

 @{b}1.@{ub} Go into SystemEditor/Doors. A new window appears. Here you must define
    first the name of the door (Door Call Name) to start it from the FAME BBS
    prompt. If you enter a name which already exists, the according datas are
    loaded automatically. For our example we use the Door Call Name '@{b}O@{ub}'.

 @{b}2.@{ub} Now define how this command should be started, three different types 
    currently exists:

           BBSCMD @{b}-@{ub} Command could be started in every conference
           SYSCMD @{b}-@{ub} Command couldn't be started by an user, they will be
                    started by FAME only.
       CONF<x>CMD @{b}-@{ub} Command could only be started in conference <x>.

    For our example, we take the BBSCMD command option, which is default.
    If you are using the CONF<x>CMD option, the conf field will be available
    and you have to enter the conference number from which your command
    should be started.

 @{b}3.@{ub} Now type in the path of the door or use the button on the right side of
    the Door Path field. This pops up a filerequester from which you could
     choose the path to the door. Note that resident Doors don't have a path,
    if you want to use doors which will be loaded resident, enter only the
    @{fg fill}NAME@{fg text} of the door without path, so ADOS will search first the resident
    list before loading it from disk.

 @{b}4.@{ub} The Stack Size and Priority fields could be leaved unchanged, as most
    doors set their stacksize itself when starting the program, and the 
    priority of 0 is the best setting for most doors during the Multi-
    tasking of AMIGA. Higher priorities prevents other tasks from getting
    the CPU, so use this field only if you require for the according door
    a high amount of CPU-Usage, i.e. for a DupeChecker door.

 @{b}5.@{ub} The accesslevel field is used to lock specific doors from users which
    shouldn't start the door. If you use i.e. a SysOp-Download door, only
    your CoSysOps should be able to use this, so you set the accesslevel for
    the DS command to the accesslevel of your CoSysOps. If an user with a
    lower accesslevel tries to start DS, FAME aborts and prints an error
    message to the user, so he'll know that he has not the right accesslevel
    to use this door. For our example, the pAGE-mASTER, we recommend the 
    accesslevel of your NewUser-Settings, so NewUsers are also able to page
    you! Default-setting is 10.

 @{b}6.@{ub} The Password field could be used to protect the door with a password.
    Upto 20 chars are allowed for the password. If you use it, the user
    will be prompted for the password before the door will be executed. If
    the password is wrong, the door won't be executed. For our example we
    leave this field empty.

 @{b}7.@{ub} The Name at Server field could be used to print a specific message in
    the Server's @{"Action Field" LINK "SERVER.GUIDE/MAIN_WINDOW"}. Most programs write their own action strings
    into this field, so it's not neccessary to enter anything here. If a
    program won't write anything in this field and you define nothing here,
    the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} will write the Door Call Name into the Action field. For our
    example we write '@{fg fill}Paging SysOp...@{fg text}' into this field.

 @{b}8.@{ub} The @{fg fill}Internal@{fg text} / @{fg fill}Menu@{fg text} checkmarks allows you to redefine internal commands
    or menucommands. If you want to use i.e. the command DOSSHELL to start
    the internal FAMEShell, set the Internal Checkmark to on and enter as
    internal command 'SHELL'. After saving, you are now able to start the
    SHELL by entering DOSSHELL. Same goes for menu, but this is currently
    not implemented and shouldn't be used! For our example, we leave this
    gadgets unselected, because we want to use an external door.

 @{b}9.@{ub} Command allow Gadgets are used to lock specific types of doorcommands.
    FAME Doorcommands are seperated in command sets, and with this buttons
    you could switch off the using of a specific command set. Take a look
    to the @{"FAMECommands.guide" LINK "FAMECOMMANDS.GUIDE/DOORLIST"} for an overview of all existing commands and
    the meaning of the shortcuts used here. If you don't have any infos
    which commands a door uses, activate all and everything will work, but
    you may also deactivate all command-sets and check out which error-codes
    the door returns when starting it. For our example (pAGE-mASTER) we have
    to activate @{fg fill}NR@{fg text}, @{fg fill}AR@{fg text}, @{fg fill}CF@{fg text},@{fg fill}RD@{fg text} and @{fg fill}SR@{fg text}.

@{b}10.@{ub} Finally you must setup the @{u}Interface Module Type@{uu}. Please refer to the 
    documentation of the according doors to determine which type of door it
    is. The following types are currently supported by FAME:

      FIM @{b}-@{ub} FAME only doors. Use this setting for our example.
      XIM @{b}-@{ub} Doors which supports the given DoorPort set in the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}
            under DoorPortNames/XIMDoorPort. 
      TIM @{b}-@{ub} Paragondoor support. Requires the Paragondoor program in the
            directory 'FAME:Modules/'.
      AIM @{b}-@{ub} Arexx Interface. Not really finished yet.
      CIM @{b}-@{ub} ?
      RIM @{b}-@{ub} RIP graphics. Not supported yet.
      SIM @{b}-@{ub} FAME Scripts. Not supported yet.
      TXT @{b}-@{ub} Shows a textfile given under DoorPath. Maybe also a MCI-Text.
      SND @{b}-@{ub} ?
      SPK @{b}-@{ub} ?
      GFM @{b}-@{ub} ?
   
    The option @{fg fill}SingleNode@{fg text} / @{fg fill}MultiNode@{fg text} allows you to choose if the door should
    be started on all Nodes at the same time or if it's only allowed to start
    it on one Node. For our example you could set it to Multi Node.

@{b}11.@{ub} Now click on Save and that's it. You could now check out your new door by
    typing the Door Call Name in the main prompt of FAME.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "FileCheckerInstall" "How to built in the FileCheckers"

                    @{b}How to built in the FileCheckers of FAME
                   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

This chapter describes how to add new filecheckers to FAME. The filecheckers
will be used to check the uploaded files for errors or corrupted archives.
To identify the fileformat of the uploaded files, the FileID.library from
BloodRock will be used. If FAME founds a format which it doesn't supports,
it switchs back to the file-extension indentification, meaning FAME checks
the filetype by identifying the file-extension.

Here's a brief description how to built in new checkers.

 @{b}1.@{ub} Choose the extension of the checker you want to built in, i.e. DMS for
    DMS-archives. If your needed extension is not in the cycle list, select
    the NEW button and enter the extension (only extension without '.').
    Also to edit other filecheckers you may use the popup-button to load in
    custom filechecker settings.

 @{b}2.@{ub} Now type in the path to the according filechecker or use again the popup-
    button to choose the path via a file-requester. If you use the according
    packer resident, enter only the filename without the path, as resident
    programs have no path anymore after they have been loaded into memory.

 @{b}3.@{ub} Now type in the Stacksize and priority of the filechecker, recommended
    sizes are stack = 10000 and priority = 0, as this settings doesn't 
    confuse the AmigaOS. If some of your packers crashes, try higher stack
    sizes, because some packers are using a high amount of stackmemory and
    if not enough stacksize is available, those programs crashes in most 
    cases.

 @{b}4.@{ub} In the Optionsfield you have to enter the required options for the
    checker. In most cases the t or -t option has to be given, but please
    take a look to the checker manuals for further information about all
    options supported.

 @{b}5.@{ub} The Error 1-5 fields are used to allow FAME to recognize errors. If an
    archive is corrupt, the packer prints out an errormessage why the 
    testing failed. You have to write the excact errorstring of the packer
    into this field, as FAME (and most other BBS-Programs, too) identifies
    errors by string-comparing the current output of the checker with the
    string(s) you've typed here, i.e. ERROR 1=Archive Corrupt!

 @{b}6.@{ub} Before using your new built-in checker, make sure that the cycle gadget
    '@{fg fill}Checker@{fg text}'Āis set to ON for your new defined checker, otherwise FAME
    won't use your checker !

 @{b}7.@{ub} The FileID Extractor and FidEx Stack Size fields are used to allow FAME
    to perform background filechecking while you are still uploading! Here 
    you have to enter a packer/extractor which is able to extract single
    files from the archive you are currently editing. Two parameters are 
    available to customize the parms, they are:

               %F @{b}-@{ub} From file: the current archive to test.
               %W @{b}-@{ub} Work Path: where to extract the fileid.

    So to allow LHA archives beeing tested while you are still uploading more
    files, use this setting (as example):

                       C:LHA -q e %F FILE_ID.DIZ %W

    So after the first complete upload of a lha-archive, FAME will process
    this file and tests/extracts the FILE_ID.DIZ, so everything is done when
    you are ready with your upload.

            @{i}That's all for installing/editing the FileCheckers.@{ui}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "NeededConfig" "Needed Configuration"

                      @{b}Needed Configuration (Requirements)
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

        First : - FAME memory usage depends on the amount of nodes.
                - The whole BBS is completely hardware-depended, meaning
                  that the only limit FAME has is your computer equipment!

      General : - Amiga (500/600/1200/2000/2500/3000/4000(T))
                - AmigaOS 2.04 (3.x will be the perfect one)
                - A minimum free memory of 1 MB
                - Workbench
                - Modem (14.4k)
                - Harddisk
                - 3/5 MB free space on the harddisk for installation.
                - Somewhat about a minimum of 5 MB free space on the harddisk
                  for file transfers.

    Multinode : - 680x0+
                - More free memory, about 500kb for each new node or about
                  150kb if loaded resident.


                  You should always have some free memory for temporõry
                  usages. If you calculate with 500kb each node if loaded
                  resident it would be a good choice.

@endnode

