@REM==============================================================================

@node "MultiFaceCard" "MultiFaceCard II & III"

                             @{b}MultiFaceCard II & III
                            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The MultiFaceCard is making trouble when opening/closing the duart.device
in different units at the same time. Normally at the first time or at the
latest at the second time when more than one units will be opened your
computer gurus.

I dont really know, but it could be that many other serial cards could also
have the same problem. However, this problem has been soluted under FAME.

Every node which wants to open/close the serial driver must set a request
to the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} what means the node has to get a permission from the @{"Server" link "InternModules"}
first. The @{"Server" link "InternModules"} handles the requests from the nodes which wants to
initialize so it's very save and will work with all serial cards which have
this problem with the device.

Also a mixture of different devices is no longer a problem of incompatibility.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Vector" "Vector"

                                  @{b}Vector Card
                                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Unlike other serial devices, the vectorser.device rejects all serial requests
that  are  bigger than the set 'Receive Buffer'.  These requests are rejected
with 'Error 4', that is 'SerErr_BufErr' from devices/serial.h.

Please ensure that the buffer setting in the VectorSer prefs program isn't
lower than the buffer in Sys:Prefs/Serial, else you will get errors on file-
transfers.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "BSCISDN" "BSC ISDN Master Card"

                              @{b}BSC ISDN Master Card
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

It's important for the bscisdn.device that you have a correct init string
configured.

You must not use "ATH1" in the init string!

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "FAMEFeatures" "Features of FAME"

                                @{b}Features of FAME
                               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

 - One of the fastest Mailbox programs available.

   Written in optimized SAS/C code.
   No usage of compiler specific commands wherever this is possible.
   Intensive usage of AmigaOS library calls. What isn't available in the OS
   will be included in high optimized asm code located in the FAME.library.

   Mark our words, if something is coded in assembler this is not a guarranty
   that it's also the fastest ever. Coding in asm is not the problem, but it's
   very hard if someone writes good and high optimized asm code, such as the
   code Bloodrock writes. If he writes asm code it takes very long and the
   reason is clear, programming in asm takes time if you don't want to produce
   buggy and also slow asm code. Good coded C code is faster and better than
   bad coded asm code. To keep development time shorter we decided to combine
   both good and fast C code with high optimized assembler code.

 - Style guide conform.

 - No hacks and no backdoors.
   FAME is coded totally system friendly.

 - A very powerful (FIM) doorport with about 1000 commands.

 - FIM door, XIM door, Paragon door, rexx door and more supported.

 - Very powerful doors included as a part of FAME and in the full version.

   FAMEChat: Full/Line-screen chat written in high optimized asm with many
             features, for more details read FAMEChat.guide.

   FAMEFullEd: It's origins are based on unix emacs.
               Very fast and written in Amiga-E.
               Yank buffer and integrated script language included.

 - Developer tools like FAMESwitchWindow.

 - No hanging doors, you can easily drop them if they hang.
   Very helpful for door coder.

 - Enhanced (more) XIM commands.

 - Publicscreen support.

 - External MUI based @{"UserEditor" link "InternModules"}.

 - One of the best and well known developer teams in business:

   - ByteAndi/tRSi
   - SieGeL/tRSi
   - dR.dRE!/tRSi
   - Spy/tRSi
   - Beatnik/tRSi
   - Bloodrock/tRSi
   - Strider/tRSi (ups, that's me)

   (tRSi-iNNOVAtiONs) consists of some more guys, but they are not in the
   FAME Developer Team.

 - Guidelines, structures, sources, definations, includes and many more
   available for door/tool coder in C, AmigaE and asm.

 - Complete hardware depending what means that if you have more and better
   hardware you can do more and more with FAME.
   The only limit FAME has is your computer-equipment and no lame arrays!

 - FAME uses everywhere dynamical lists, in some parts bi-directional and
   more-dimensional. Because of this FAME uses no megabytes of memory and
   is also very fast.

 - No real limitations in conferences, nodes and many more.
   Because of the fact that FAME uses everywhere lists there are no real
   limits. The only limits are long-variable sizes (about 2 gigs).
   The number of nodes and conferences are for example long-size dependet
   what means more than 2 billion nodes and conferences are possible.
   From the technical point of view they are unlimited, or do you own
   hundrets of giga byte ram? Apart from the fact that no 32 bit computer
   could handle such ram areas.

 - RAM usage is situation depending, because of the dynamical lists.

 - Each node uses about 500 kb memory and about 150 kb if loaded resident.

 - All executables a reentrable, means they can be loaded resident into
   memory. Not needed for @{"Server" link "InternModules"} and @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}, because they are
   commodities, but it's also possible.

 - Coded to avoid memory fragmentations.

 - Full xpr library protocol support and nevertheless @{"MainPart" link "InternModules"} can be loaded
   resident.

 - FAME Hydra implementation with ASL Filerequester process and this of
   course while @{"FAMEHydra" link "FAMEHydra.guide/Main"} can be loaded resident.

 - Complete gadtools driven @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}, no icons or text files.

 - FAME uses more than 15 own and some OS lists.

 - FAME exists of more than 40 different structures.

 - FAME uses a very handy and powerful @{"Server" link "InternModules"} to control the whole BBS and
   all nodes.

 - @{"Server" link "InternModules"} and @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} are commodities.
   You can easy find iconified or back clicked windows. Hot-key usage.

 - Intelligent and/or more hidden features like a real shell like history,
   an intelligent argument parser which understands commands and arguments
   although you have typed too much spaces between, before and/or commands
   and arguments, possibillity to edit in strings with cursor keys and many
   other like saving flagged files after carrier loss, ...

 - Red/White swap for users and serial output.

 - Own FAME.libray coded in high optimized assembler.
   Many nice and useful functions like string, memory and many other
   miscellaneous functions. Often ANSI-C replacement functions or simple
   missing OS funtions, for example memory pool functions
   (also under OS 2.x).

 - Many information sources like ports, FAMESemaphore and lists.

 - Powerful ToolPort to interact with FAME and tools (Not free yet).

 - Directory executions at FAME start, end, logon, logoff, for batches and
   tools for easy handling of bulletin tools and external tools like
   FAMECoProcesses.

 - FAMECoProcess to start tools which follows special guideline defines
   on different configured times to handle background stuff.

 - Background file checking, file_id.diz handling and file posting.

 - Most configurable mailbox program currently available.
   FAME User.Data currently has more than 116 different options.
   Hundrets of configurable options for the whole BBS.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "FuturePlans" "Future Plans"

                                  @{b}Future Plans
                                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

 - FAME ToolPort for external action depending processes and tools.
   Including event handlers.

 - Different network systems and internet support.

 - DoorHelp. Viewing of AmigaGuide files via Console/Serial.

 - FAX recognition.

 - External message and file systems.

 - Additional always open DoorPort for external tools to access a node
   to get/set datas and use internal functions i.e. to post mail and
   for asynchron doors.

The future plans are short, because we have build in most of our ideas
and features. The real future plans list depends on you.

Nearly everything you and the other registered customers of FAME are
suggesting will be implemented if it makes sense and we have the time
for that.

Your ideas and suggestions are welcome.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "ThinkAbout" "Think About"

                                  @{b}Think About
                                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

 - Siegel/tRSi holds the record with the highest online time of FAME with
   135 hours (more than 5 days). The really highest online time is not
   written down. It was some weeks in new-year 96 where Siegel/tRSi wasn't
   coding.

@endnode

