@REM==============================================================================

@node "Commands" "Commands"

                             @{b}Internal Menu Commands
                            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

   @{"  W  " link "Commands_W"} - The W Command (User Settings)


                     @{"Other commands are not implemented yet" link "NotImplemented"}

    See the files in 'FAME:Help/' for first information about the commands!

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Commands_W" "The W Command (User Settings)"

                         @{b}The W Command (User Settings)
                        ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

The @{fg fill}W@{fg text} Command (entered without arguments) starts the User Setup Editor.
Now you'll see your current personal user setup. The prompt asks for a
number to change. The numbers in the rectangle brackets are the ones you
may choose now. (No need to say that the brackets don't need to be typed here).
Hitting @{fg fill}Return@{fg text}/@{fg fill}Enter@{fg text} (no input) quits the User Setup Editor.
Entering invalid numbers won't have any effect.

Some fields may be disabled for you. This depends on the SysOp's settings
(for example, changing the user name is often forbidden).

What you'll see first looks like this:


                         -+ MAIN USER CONFIGURATION +-                   
                                                                         
@{"[ 1]" link W_1} NAME                  : @{fg fill}BLOODROCK@{fg text}
@{"[ 2]" link W_2} PASSWORD              : @{fg fill}naaah. :^(@{fg text}
@{"[ 3]" link W_3} LOCATION              : @{fg fill}(tRSi/F-Innovation)@{fg text}
@{"[ 4]" link W_4} FROM                  : @{fg fill}Berlin@{fg text}
@{"[ 5]" link W_5} PHONE NUMBER          : @{fg fill}nah-naaah.@{fg text}
@{"[ 6]" link W_6} COMPUTER              : @{fg fill}Amiga 4000@{fg text}
@{"[ 7]" link W_7} MODEM                 : @{fg fill}USR V.34@{fg text}
@{"[ 8]" link W_8} NUMBER OF LINES       : @{fg fill}50@{fg text}
@{"[ 9]" link W_9} SCREEN TYPE           : @{fg fill}TXT@{fg text}
@{"[10]" link W_10} TEXT TYPE/LANGUAGE   : @{fg fill}English@{fg text}
@{"[11]" link W_11} EDITOR TYPE          : @{fg fill}FULLSCREEN  EDITOR@{fg text}
@{"[12]" link W_12} GENERAL M/F SCANNING : @{fg fill}MAIL/FILE SCAN@{fg text}

@{"[13]" link W_13} ADDITIONAL OPTIONS  @{"[14]" link W_14} DOOR CONFIG         @{"[15]" link W_15} CONFERENCE OPTIONS
@{"[16]" link W_16} CONFERENCE FLAGS    @{"[17]" link W_17} COMMUNICATION OPTS  @{"[18]" link W_18} TRANSFER OPTIONS  
@{"[19]" link W_19} ADD MESSAGE OPTIONS                                                 
                                                                         
Enter Number to change (@{fg shine}Enter@{fg text})@{fg fill}Quit >@{fg shine}:@{fg text} @{bg fill} @{bg back}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_1 "User Settings: 1"

Command: W 1
Setup:   Name

Asks for your User Name or Handle. Do not ever change your name if this isn't
really needed. Other users who often write messages to you will no doubt be
grateful. User Names must be at least 3 and at most 30 chars long.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_2 "User Settings: 2"

Command: W 2
Setup:   Password

Asks for your new password to use. You won't see what you type. Every char
you type gets echoed as an asterisk (@{fg fill}*@{fg text}) char. Because you can't see if you
made any mistake, FAME asks you to enter the same password again. Only if
both passwords are equal, the new password is accepted. Otherwise, nothing
was changed. Passwords must be at least 3 and at most 20 chars long.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_3 "User Settings: 3"

Command: W 3
Setup:   Location

Asks for your new location string. Enter @{fg fill}Berlin@{fg text} or such. Scene people often
insert their group or BBS name here. Location strings must be at least 3 and
at most 30 chars long.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_4 "User Settings: 4"

Command: W 4
Setup:   From

Another location-like field. Insert your city or country here, or what your
SysOp wants you to. From strings must be at least 3 and at most 20 chars long.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_5 "User Settings: 5"

Command: W 5
Setup:   Phone Number

Asks for your telephone number the SysOp may reach you for emergency reasons.
Telephone numbers must be at least 3 and at most 15 chars long.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_6 "User Settings: 6"

Command: W 6
Setup:   Computer

Displays a list of computer types. Choose one by typing the matching number.
Entering custom text is not allowed. If your computer isn't listed, engage
your SysOp to add some more computer types to the list.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_7 "User Settings: 7"

Command: W 7
Setup:   Modem

Displays a list of modem types. Choose one by typing the matching number.
Entering custom text is not allowed. If your modem isn't listed, engage
your SysOp to add some more modem types to the list.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_8 "User Settings: 8"

Command: W 8
Setup:   Number Of Lines

You'll see numbers printed, downward-counted from 100 on. Below, a prompt
appears, asking for the highest visible number (on top of your screen).
This value is used by FAME and it's doors for pause prompts, or for screen
layouting. For example, FAMEChat and FAMEFullEd make use of it.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_9 "User Settings: 9"

Command: W 9
Setup:   Screen Type

Displays a list of available screen types. The screen type settings specify
the text screens you prefer. Text screens are SysOp edited screens, or
bulletin texts. These texts may come up in different languages. Choose
your favourite screen text language by selecting an appendix (for example,
@{fg fill}.TXT@{fg text} or @{fg fill}.GER@{fg text}) by entering the according number.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_10 "User Settings: 10"

Command: W 10
Setup:   Text Type/Language

Displays a list of available languages. This setup may used by FAME and all
FAME doors (doors mostly don't support this) to communicate with you in the
correct language. Enter the according number of your preferred language.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_11 "User Settings: 11"

Command: W 11
Setup:   Editor Type

The editor types are available for message and other text editing:

[ 1] LINE EDITOR             - Simple and primitive line editor.
                               Not a good choice for a demanding user.
[ 2] FULLSCREEN EDITOR       - Full-featured, comfortable full screen
                               editor.
[ 3] EXTERNAL EDITOR         - If your SysOp has installed an additional
                               text editor, you may choose it here.
[ 4] PROMPT FOR EDITOR TYPE  - Everytime you're going to edit a text,
                               FAME will ask you what editor type to
                               use. Nerve-racking after a while.

And again, the according number wins the race.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_12 "User Settings: 12"

Command: W 12
Setup:   General Mail/File Scanning

When logging in, FAME may check for new files and/or mails since your last
call. This one offers the following choices:

[ 1] NO SCANNING             - Don't scan for anything.
[ 2] MAIL/FILE SCANNING      - Scan for both new files and new mails.
[ 3] MAIL SCANNING           - Scan for new mails only.
[ 4] FILE SCANNING           - Scan for new files only.
[ 5] PROMPT BEFORE SCANNING  - Offer the choice everytime you log on.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_13 "User Settings: 13"

Command: W 13
Setup:   Additional Options

[ 1] ZOOM TYPE               - Not implemented yet.
[ 2] HIDDEN FOR WHO/CHAT     - Yes or No. Yes means that anybody who
                               wants to see who is online will only
                               see @{b}Hidden / Do not disturb!@{ub} instead
                               of your name and location.
[ 3] BIRTHDAY                - Your day of birth. Optional. If you fill-in
                               this field, you may be surprised if you
                               log on at your birthday (depends on your
                               SysOp what will happen then). Format is
                               @{fg fill}MM-DD-YY@{fg text} (month/day/year).
[ 4] LOGON JOIN CONF         - The conference number you want to join
                               everytime when logging on. If you enter
                               nothing here, you'll always auto-join to the
                               conference you were before your last logoff.
[ 5] MSG SCREEN CLEAR        - Yes or No. Yes means that while you're
                               reading messages, the screen gets cleared
                               before a new message is displayed. Useful
                               for people who's terminal program is running
                               on a slow Amiga in productivity mode with
                               many colours.
[ 6] FILE SCREEN CLEAR       - Same as MSG Screen Clear; Yes or No. States
                               if the screen shall be cleared after a text
                               page is completed when viewing file lists.
[ 7] DEFAULT UPLOAD          - Not implemented yet.
[ 8] DEFAULT DOWNLOAD        - Your @{fg fill}D@{fg text} command setup. Everytime you start
                               downloading using the @{fg fill}D@{fg text} command, one of the
                               two @{fg fill}DL@{fg text} or @{fg fill}DG@{fg text} commands is executed instead.
                               @{fg fill}D@{fg text} is just a command alias. @{fg fill}DL@{fg text} stands for
                               @{b}Download flagged files in current
                               conference@{ub},
                               @{fg fill}DG@{fg text} means @{b}global download across conferences@{ub}.
[ 9] ANSI MODUS              - Turns ANSI colours on or off. The third
                               choice is having FAME asking this question
                               everytime you log on. Nerve-racking after
                               a while.
[10] MENU PROMPT             - At this point you may change your BBS main
                               prompt to your needs. For the many different
                               information strings you may add, several
                               MCI type commands are available. You'll
                               only see a list of most important commands
                               needed for prompts. For further commands
                               please refer to the MCI commands documen-
                               tation. If you have modified your prompt up
                               to total confusion, just enter nothing here
                               to reset your Main Prompt back to the FAME
                               default prompt.
[11] SHELL NUMLINES          - Sets the number of lines for FAME online
                               Shell windows (only interesting if you're
                               allowed by the SysOp to use a Shell).
[12] RED/WHITE SWAP          - @{fg fill}RED@{fg text}/@{fg shine}WHITE@{fg text} should appear correct, meaning
                               that @{fg fill}RED@{fg text} should be red and @{fg shine}WHITE@{fg text} should be
                               white. Because nobody takes care of the
                               correct ANSI colour definitions, most doors
                               currently use [37m for red colour, which
                               is WRONG. Due to this, FAME also uses [37m
                               for red and [31m for white by default. Some
                               terminal programs may have problems with this
                               setup. With this option you may adjust your
                               red/white setup.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_14 "User Settings: 14"

Command: W 14
Setup:   Door Config

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_15 "User Settings: 15"

Command: W 15
Setup:   Conference Options

Here you may set up several conference-related things. This is a replacement
for the @{fg fill}W 16@{fg text} command. Here you may also specify some additional things.

[ 1] CONF USERNAME      - You may specify another user alias name to use
                          for each conference when joining to.
[ 2] NEW MAIL SCANNING  - New mail scanner flag. If set to NO, all mail scans
                          will exclude that conference.
[ 3] NEW FILE SCANNING  - Same as @{b}New Mail Scanning@{ub}, but for files.
[ 4] ZOOMING            - Not implemented yet.
[ 5] CONF ACCESS        - You may deny yourself any conference access. This
                          might be useful if you don't want to get fed up by
                          e.g. a custom file scanner which doesn't behave
                          correct and always scans and displays all wanted
                          and unwanted conferences.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_16 "User Settings: 16"

Command: W 16
Setup:   Conference Flags

For those who dislike the @{fg fill}W 15@{fg text} command, this one is a replacement function,
but it doesn't offer all possibe conference settings. For complete conference
editing, @{fg fill}W 15@{fg text} was the better choice.

You may specify your conference-related File/Mail scanning and message zooming
flags here. WYSIWYMG (What you see is what you might get):

@{b}Number M F Z ConferenceName                 Number M F Z ConferenceName
------ - - - -------------------------   ------ - - - -------------------------@{ub}
   (@{fg fill}1@{fg text}) @{fg shine}* *@{fg text}   Basement                            (@{fg fill}2@{fg text})   @{fg shine}*@{fg text}   First Floor
   (@{fg fill}3@{fg text})     @{fg shine}*@{fg text} Household and Toys


You'll get prompted like this:

Enter Flag Type: (@{fg fill}M@{fg text})ailScan (@{fg fill}F@{fg text})ileScan (@{fg fill}Z@{fg text})oom >: @{bg fill} @{bg back}

Enter @{fg fill}M@{fg text} for editing the message scan flags, @{fg fill}F@{fg text} for the file scanning flags and
@{fg fill}Z@{fg text} for message zooming setup (zooming is not implemted yet).

After selecting an flag group, the next prompt asks you for the conferences
you want to change:

Choose: @{fg fill}Number@{fg text} or (@{fg fill}+@{fg text})Flag all (@{fg fill}*@{fg text})Toggle all (@{fg fill}-@{fg text})Unflag all @{fg fill}>@{fg text}: @{bg fill} @{bg back}

-where @{fg fill}*@{fg text} toggles all flags, @{fg fill}+@{fg text} sets and @{fg fill}-@{fg text} deletes all flags. If you want to
change only a single conference, type in it's number instead.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_17 "User Settings: 17"

Command: W 17
Setup:   Communication Options

This page lists several things you may do at the BBS and states if you want
to have online message receiving on or off for this moment. If turned off,
FAME waits until you change to another action where online message receiving
is allowed and then outstanding OLMs are displayed.

There are some phases where you never receive OLMs; for example, when you're
executing a SysOp command or a file transfer is running.

While in idle mode (at the main prompt), OLMs are always enabled.

[ 1] EVERY OTHER PHASE IS SET TO A DEFAULT VALUE:

[ 2] BBSHELP             [ 3] BULLETINS           [ 4] CHANGESTATS
[ 5] ENTEREALL           [ 6] FILELISTING         [ 7] FLAGEDIT
[ 8] JOINCONF            [ 9] LOGGINGON           [10] MULTICHAT
[11] NEWFILES            [12] PREPAREDOWNL        [13] PREPAREUPL
[14] READMAIL            [15] SCANFILES           [16] SCANMAIL
[17] SEARCHFOR           [18] SHELL               [19] SYSOPCHAT
[20] SYSOPCOMMENT        [21] VIEWFILES           [22] VIEWTEXT
[23] WAITFORKEY          [24] WHO                 [25] WRITEMAIL

(@{fg fill}YES@{fg text} means receiving is turned on and vice versa)

Number 1 stands for anything not listed here. You should turn off OLM
receiving here (@{fg fill}NO@{fg text}) in order not to have trashed screens when using a
door which isn't able to refresh the screen display.

By entering @{fg fill}+@{fg text} or @{fg fill}-@{fg text} instead of a number, you may toggle all fields on or off,
with @{fg fill}*@{fg text} you may toggle (inverse) all entries.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_18 "User Settings: 18"

Command: W 18
Setup:   Transfer Options

Here you may specify which transfer protocols to use for several file
transfer action. Transfer protocols check all transferred data for errors.
Some of the most common transfer protocols are ZModem, @{"FAMEHydra" link "FAMEHydra.guide/Main"} or YModem,
for example. Except Default Protocol, every protocol setup offers the
choice of prompting for a protocol everytime you start a file transfer.


[ 1] DEFAULT PROTOCOL     - Default protocol to use in situations not
                            listed here.
[ 2] BEGIN UPLOAD         - When beginning a file upload.
[ 3] BEGIN DOWNLOAD       - When beginning a download.
[ 4] MESSAGE ATTACH UL    - When sending attached file(s) with a message.
[ 5] MESSAGE ATTACH DL    - When downloading message attached file(s).
[ 6] DOOR FILE UPLOAD     - When uploading a file from within a door.
[ 7] DOOR FILE DOWNLOAD   - When downloading a file from within a door.
[ 8] USER XPR BLOCK SIZE  - You may specify your XPR block size for
                            file transfers. Please refer to your XPR
                            documentation and to the manual for your
                            Terminal program. Most common buffer size
                            is 1024 bytes, but higher values may raise
                            transfer speed a little bit.
[ 9] FILECHECK PROCESS    - Two possible setups: @{fg fill}After Upload@{fg text} or
                            @{fg fill}Background Check@{fg text}. Files you uploaded get
                            checked by the BBS for errors, duplicate
                            uploads, file_id.diz, virus infection or
                            whatever more. @{fg fill}Background Check@{fg text} is the
                            default. That means that if you're uploading
                            several files, every transferred file is
                            checked immediately while FAME receives
                            the next file(s). This saves much time
                            for you (as the user) after a large upload
                            is completed. @{fg shine}After Upload@{fg text} means that all
                            files get checked after the whole file
                            transfer was completed. Rarely used since
                            background checking is implemented..

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node W_19 "User Settings: 19"

Command: W 19
Setup:   Additional Message Options

[ 1] MSG ROOMING           - Specifies if you wish that the message
                             LineEditor shall work in auto-indent mode.
[ 2] ASCII MSG             - Suppresses line numbers in the message
                             LineEditor. Also, if you enter an empty
                             line, you won't get ejected to the message
                             options prompt. @{b}Msg Rooming@{ub} is also turned
                             off. Useful if you want to snap texts in.
                             Not useful if you don't use the LineEditor.
[ 3] MESSAGE QUOTE         - You may have FAME always quoting the whole
                             original message to your reply message if
                             @{fg fill}Quote All@{fg text} is choosen. @{fg fill}Prompt For Quoting@{fg text}
                             will always ask if you want to quote and
                             which text lines to be quoted. Users who
                             prefer the Full Screen Editor should select
                             @{fg fill}Quote All@{fg text} and cut unwanted text from within
                             the editor, which is much easier and more
                             comfortable. In addition, you're never asked
                             again and again if you want to use quotes.
[ 4] PRIVATE ON REPLY      - When replying a message, FAME normally asks
                             if the reply message should be of the same
                             private/public type. Two choices are possible
                             here. @{fg fill}Keep Private Status@{fg text} will use the same
                             private/public state for the reply message
                             as the original message status, and @{fg fill}Prompt
                             For Private Status@{fg text} will prompt everytime
                             you reply a message. Nerve-racking after a
                             while..
[ 5] MSG SUBJECT ON REPLY  - With this option you may specify if you
                             always want to keep a message subject, or
                             if you want to change message subjects for
                             the reply mail.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "InternUserEd" "The Internal User Editor"

                            @{b}The Internal User Editor
                           ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

                                @{" General Things " link InUsEd_General}

                 @{"    Usernumber  :" link InUsEd_UserNumber} ...         @{"    UserStatus  :" link InUsEd_UserStatus} ...
                 @{"(A) Username   >:" link InUsEd_UserName} ...         @{"(B) Userlevel  >:" link InUsEd_UserLevel} ...
                 @{"(E) Location   >:" link InUsEd_Location} ...         @{"(F) Spy        >:" link InUsEd_Spy} ...
                 @{"(G) From       >:" link InUsEd_From} ...         @{"(H) UserPhone  >:" link InUsEd_UserPhone} ...
                 @{"(J) Password   >:" link InUsEd_Password} ...         @{"(K) AllHacks   >:" link InUsEd_AllHacks} ...
                 @{"(L) ConfAccess >:" link InUsEd_ConfAccess} ...         @{"(O) LastHacks  >:" link InUsEd_LastHack} ...
                 @{"(P) Ratio      >:" link InUsEd_Ratio} ...         @{"(T) RatioType  >:" link InUsEd_RatioType} ...
                 @{"(U) LosCarrier >:" link InUsEd_LosCarrier} ...         @{"(V) Calls      >:" link InUsEd_Calls} ...
                 @{"(W) Uploads    >:" link InUsEd_Uploads} ...         @{"(X) Downloads  >:" link InUsEd_Downloads} ...
                 @{"(Y) BytesUpload>:" link InUsEd_BytesUpload} ...         @{"(Z) BytesDownl.>:" link InUsEd_ByteDownl} ...
                 @{"(?) D.ByteLimit>:" link InUsEd_DByteLimit} ...         @{"(*) D.FileLimit>:" link InUsEd_DFileLimit} ...
                 @{"(,) D.ByteBonus>:" link InUsEd_DByteBonus} ...         @{"(.) D.FileBonus>:" link InUsEd_DFileBonus} ...
                 @{"(;) D.ByteDl   >:" link InUsEd_DByteDl} ...         @{"(:) D.FileDl   >:" link InUsEd_DFileDl} ...
                 @{"(#) MesgWrite  >:" link InUsEd_MesgWrite} ...         @{"(^) MessageRead>:" link InUsEd_MessageRead} ...
                 @{"([) LastConf   >:" link InUsEd_LastConf} ...         @{"(]) CnfReJoin  >:" link InUsEd_CnfRejoin} ...
                 @{"( ) TimeLimit  >:" link InUsEd_TimeLimit} ...         @{"( ) NumLines   >:" link InUsEd_NumLines} ...
                 @{"(<) TimeUsed   >:" link InUsEd_TimeUsed} ...         @{"(>) BAUD       >:" link InUsEd_Baud} ...
                 @{"(/) HighCPSUp  >:" link InUsEd_HighCPSUp} ...         @{"(\) HighCPSDown>:" link InUsEd_HighCPSDown} ...

@{"(S)ave" link InUsEd_Save} @{"(R)eactive" link InUsEd_Reactivate} @{"(I)nactive" link InUsEd_Inactive} @{"(D)elete" link InUsEd_Delete} @{"(N)ewUser" link InUsEd_NewUser} @{"(M)MoreData" link InUsEd_MoreData} @{"(0-9)Presets" link InUsEd_Presets}

@{"(C)onferences" link InUsEd_Conferences} @{"(TAB) ConfAccess" link InUsEd_TabConfAccess} @{"(+/-)=Next/Prev. User" link InUsEd_NextPrevUser} @{"(Q)uit" link InUsEd_Quit} @{"Status:" link InUsEd_Status}

@{b}NOTE:@{ub}

 - If you do a newuser scan the scanner always skips the SysOp means it will
   begin from user number 2 with the newuser scanning.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_General "Internal User Editor: General"

The internal user editor is commonly used for quick online user editing.
If you want to edit more than one user, i'd highly recommend the Module User
Editor, which is more comfortable and will protect your eyes. :^)

Fields are chosen by walking around with the cursor keys and hitting Return/
Enter then; or by using their shortcut key as found in brackets left to the
field name.

  Note: the AmigaGuide gadgets in the main page of this Internal User Editor
  manual don't contain the brace shortcut key symbols ( @{fg fill}{@{fg text} and @{fg fill}}@{fg text} ) because some
  AmigaGuide Library/Datatype versions are buggy and misinterpret them a bit..

Some fields are text input fields, some only offer choices like @{fg fill}Yes@{fg text} or @{fg fill}No@{fg text}.
For example, the RatioType field offers three possible choices (@{fg fill}byte@{fg text}, @{fg fill}file@{fg text} or
@{fg fill}byte/file@{fg text}).

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_UserNumber "Internal User Editor: User Number"

Command: @{b}User Number@{ub}

Every FAME user has it's own user (slot-) number. FAME user data files are
sorted by slot numbers, where each Slot Number has got an assigned user (no
matter if the user is active, inactive or deleted). The slot number cannot be
changed. To assign another slot number to a user, you need to duplicate the
whole user entry to another slot.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_UserName "Internal User Editor: User Name"

Command: @{b}User Name@{ub}

Here you may modify the user's Name/Handle.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Location "Internal User Editor: Location"

Command: @{b}Location@{ub}

Here you can change the user's location string.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_From "Internal User Editor: From"

Command: @{b}From@{ub}

The user's From string..

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Password "Internal User Editor: Password"

Command: @{b}Password@{ub}

The user's personal logon password (who claims to be malicious ?)

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_ConfAccess "Internal User Editor: Conference Access"

Command: @{b}Conference Access@{ub}

This one lets you change the user's Conference Access alias/string. With
the Conference Access Alias you may set up all conference flags by one
of several presets.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Ratio "Internal User Editor: Ratio"

Command: @{b}Ratio@{ub}

Sets up how a user may download if he has uploaded something. Enter the
download ratio in conjunction to 1 uploaded unit. These units may be either
files, bytes or both. A ration of 3 means that the user may download 3 files
(or bytes) after uploading one. 

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_LosCarrier "Internal User Editor: Carrier Losses"

Command: @{b}Carrier Losses@{ub}

This field shows how often the user has logged off by simply hanging up, by
Terminal crashes at home or due to noisy phone lines.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Uploads "Internal User Editor: Uploads"

Command: @{b}Uploads@{ub}

This field states about how many files the user has uploaded all over the
time. It gets used to calculate how many files a user (with file ratio) may
download. Raising this value means extra file credits for him/her.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_BytesUpload "Internal User Editor: BytesUpload"

Command: @{b}BytesUpload@{ub}

This field states about how many bytes the user has uploaded all over the
time. It gets used to calculate how many bytes a user (with byte ratio) may
download. Raising this value means extra byte credits for him/her.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_DByteLimit "Internal User Editor: Daily Byte Limit"

Command: @{b}Daily Byte Limit@{ub}

If your BBS modem lines are used to full capacity, it may be helpful to
encourage users not to log on for extremely long periods. This option
will help you with this. :^)

This value is the amount of bytes the user may download each day, no matter
how many overall download bytes he/she has remaining.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_DByteBonus "Internal User Editor: Day's Byte Bonus"

Command: @{b}Day's Byte Bonus@{ub}

This field shows how many bonus bytes the user gained today. The bonus
multipliers are set-up with the System Editor (@{b}Conferences@{ub} part).

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_DByteDl "Internal User Editor: Day's Byte Download"

Command: @{b}Day's Byte Download@{ub}

This field shows how many bytes the user has downloaded today.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MesgWrite "Internal User Editor: Message Write"

Command: @{b}Message Write@{ub}

The total number of messages written by the user.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_LastConf "Internal User Editor: Last Conference"

Command: @{b}Last Conference@{ub}

This one shows the number of the last conference the user was in at the last
logoff.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_TimeLimit "Internal User Editor: Time Limit"

Command: @{b}Time Limit@{ub}

Time Limit is used to separate the good users from the bad ones. :^)
Some people often seem not to log off ever. Yeah, some BBS systems are
quite popular ! However, this value specifies how many minutes the user
may spend here every day.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_TimeUsed "Internal User Editor: Time Used"

Command: @{b}Time Used@{ub}

This field shows the overall amount of minutes the user has spent in visiting
your fine BBS.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_HighCPSUp "Internal User Editor: Highest Upload CPS Rate"

Command: @{b}Highest Upload CPS Rate@{ub}

Here the hi-score fan can see the highest upload rate the user had with a
file transfer.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_UserStatus "Internal User Editor: User Status"

Command: @{b}User Status@{ub}

The User Status field shows the active/inactive state of the user. This status
may be changed using the @{fg fill}R@{fg text} (Reactivate) and @{fg fill}I@{fg text} (Inactive) keys.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_UserLevel "Internal User Editor: User Level"

Command: @{b}User Level@{ub}

The User Level specifies about what the user is allowed to do here, or what
better not. In addition to several special flags, most access settings are
level-related. Values from 0 to 255 are possible, where 255 (SysOp Level)
is the highest value which always allows everything. So take care about
whom you give a user level of 255. All other levels may be freely defined.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Spy "Internal User Editor: Spy"

Command: @{b}Spy@{ub}

This flag decides if FAME shall start user capturing every time the user
logs on, and until the user logs off. Nice to have all activties of any
potential hacker well-stored when sleeping or being at work.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_UserPhone "Internal User Editor: Phone Number"

Command: @{b}Phone Number@{ub}

Some say that this might be the user's telephone number.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_AllHacks "Internal User Editor: Overall Hacks"

Command: @{b}Overall Hacks@{ub}

This field shows the user's number of login hack attempts. Normally, not the
user himself was the hacker; another user may have been trying to log in with
this user's name.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_LastHack "Internal User Editor: Last Hack"

Command: @{b}Last Hack@{ub}

This fields shows how many password hack attempts have been done since he/she
was correctly logged on the last time.

Some doors write private messages to users which had some failed password
attempts. These doors reset this value to zero after sending such messages.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_RatioType "Internal User Editor: Ratio Type"

Command: @{b}Ratio Type@{ub}

Here you may specify what kind of upload:download ratio to use for the user.

You may choose one of:

 Byte        - one uploaded byte means @{fg fill}n@{fg text} bytes free for downloading
 File        - by uploading one file the user may download @{fg fill}n@{fg text} files
 Byte/File   - both file and byte ratio must be fulfilled.

-where @{fg fill}n@{fg text} stands for the @{"ratio" link InUsEd_Ratio} value.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Calls "Internal User Editor: Calls"

Command: @{b}Calls@{ub}

This one shows how often the user had the honour to call your BBS.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Downloads "Internal User Editor: Downloaded Files"

Command: @{b}Downloaded Files@{ub}

This value is the overall amount of files the user has downloaded.
It gets used to calculate how many bytes a user (with byte ratio) may
download. Lowering this value means extra file credits for him/her.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_ByteDownl "Internal User Editor: Downloaded Bytes"

Command: @{b}Downloaded Bytes@{ub}

This huge value is the overall amount of bytes the user has downloaded.
It gets used to calculate how many bytes a user (with byte ratio) may
download. Lowering this value means extra file credits for him/her.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_DFileLimit "Internal User Editor: Daily Download File Limit"

Command: @{b}Daily Download File Limit@{ub}

This value is the amount of files the user may download each day, no matter
how many overall download bytes he/she has remaining. Good for persuading
long-term tenants to apply the brakes. :^)

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_DFileBonus "Internal User Editor: Day's File Bonus"

Command: @{b}Day's File Bonus@{ub}

This field shows how many bonus files the user gained today. The bonus
multipliers are set-up with the System Editor (@{b}Conferences@{ub} part).

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_DFileDl "Internal User Editor: DFileDL"

Command: @{b}DFileDL@{ub}

This field shows how many files the user has downloaded today.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MessageRead "Internal User Editor: MessageRead"

Command: @{b}MessageRead@{ub}

This is the total amount of messages the user has read.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_CnfRejoin "Internal User Editor: Conference Rejoin"

Command: @{b}Conference Rejoin@{ub}

This function is fully implemented right now. You may set up which conference
to join when logging in. This may be any number, or may be always the last
conference the user was before (at the last logoff).

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_NumLines "Internal User Editor: Number Of Screen Lines"

Command: @{b}Number Of Screen Lines@{ub}

Sets up the number of text lines the user has got on his/her terminal screen.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Baud "Internal User Editor: Baud Rate"

Command: @{b}Baud Rate@{ub}

This value stands for the actual connect baud rate. If the user is not
currently online, this field shows his/her last connect baud rate.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_HighCPSDown "Internal User Editor: Highest Download CPS Rate"

Command: @{b}Highest Download CPS Rate@{ub}

Shows the user's highest reached download CPS rate.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Save "Internal User Editor: Save Changes"

Command: @{b}Save Changes@{ub}

This will save all changes you actually made at the current user. Note that
you have to save a user first before you can change to another user or if
you want to leave the internal User Editor. Otherwise, your changes won't
be saved.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Reactivate "Internal User Editor: Reactivate User"

Command: @{b}Reactivate User@{ub}

This switch activates the user, if inactive.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Inactive "Internal User Editor: Inactivate User"

Command: @{b}Inactivate User@{ub}

With this flag you may put a user into inactive state without deleting the
whole account together with all user-related data.
Inactive means that the BBS will behave like as if the user wouldn't exist.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Delete "Internal User Editor: Delete User"

Command: @{b}Delete User@{ub}

This key marks a user as deleted. This flag is equal to the @{"Reactivate" link InUsEd_Reactivate} and
@{"Inactive" link InUsEd_Inactive} functions, but if a new user logs on, the deleted user slot may
be used for the new user and all data related to the deleted user is lost.

@endnode

==============================================================================

w@node InUsEd_NewUser "Internal User Editor: New User"

Command: @{b}New User@{ub}

This function toggles the @{b}User State@{ub} from @{fg fill}ValidUser@{fg text} to @{fg fill}NewUser@{fg text} and vice versa.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MoreData "Internal User Editor: More Data"

Command: @{b}More Data@{ub}

This command displays a second page to edit:

     @{"   Username :" link InUsEd_UserName}                       @{"   Usernumber :" link InUsEd_UserNumber}
     @{"   Birthday :" link InUsEd_MD_Birthday}
     @{"   ZoomType :" link InUsEd_MD_ZoomType}                       @{"   Extension  :" link InUsEd_MD_Extension}
     @{"   XferProt.:" link InUsEd_MD_XferProt}                       @{"   Language   :" link InUsEd_MD_Language}
     @{"   FirstCall:" link InUsEd_MD_FirstCall}                       @{"   CompiType  :" link InUsEd_MD_CompiType}
     @{"   LastTime :" link InUsEd_MD_LastTime}                       @{"   ModemType  :" link InUsEd_MD_ModemType}
     @{"(A)Ansi    >:" link InUsEd_MD_Ansi}                       @{"(C)NewScan   >:" link InUsEd_MD_NewScan}
     @{"(D)Hidden  >:" link InUsEd_MD_Hidden}                       @{"(E)ExpertMode>:" link InUsEd_MD_ExpertMode}
     @{"(F)FileClS >:" link InUsEd_MD_FileClS}                       @{"(G)StringEdit>:" link InUsEd_MD_StringEdit}
     @{"(H)MsgClS  >:" link InUsEd_MD_MsgClS}                       @{"(I)MsgRooming>:" link InUsEd_MD_MsgRooming}
     @{"(J)Def.Upl.>:" link InUsEd_MD_DefUpl}                       @{"(K)Def.Downl.>:" link InUsEd_MD_DefDownl}
     @{"(L)Def.View>:" link InUsEd_MD_DefView}                       @{"(M)Def. Zippy>:" link InUsEd_MD_DefZippy}
     @{"(N)FileID  >:" link InUsEd_MD_FileID}                       @{"(O)Editor    >:" link InUsEd_MD_Editor}
     @{"(P)UserFBPW>:" link InUsEd_MD_UserFBPW}                       @{"(Q)UserFileB.>:" link InUsEd_MD_UserFileBase}
     @{"(R)MsgCryPW>:" link InUsEd_MD_MsgCryPW}                       @{"(S)DoMsgCrypt>:" link InUsEd_MD_DoMsgCrypt}
     @{"(T)LowCPSD.>:" link InUsEd_MD_LowCPSD}                       @{"(U)LowCPSUp. >:" link InUsEd_MD_LowCPSUp}
     @{"(V)FileNuke>:" link InUsEd_MD_FileNuke}                       @{"(W)BytesNuked>:" link InUsEd_MD_BytesNuked}
     @{"(X)GoodBye >:" link InUsEd_MD_GoodBye}                       @{"(Y)Ascii Msg >:" link InUsEd_MD_ASCIIMsg}

     @{"(B)ack to Main Menu " link InUsEd_MD_BackToMain} @{" Status: " link InUsEd_Status}

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_Birthday "Internal User Editor: More Data / Birthday"

Command: @{b}More Data / Birthday@{ub}

Shows the user's birthday.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_ZoomType "Internal User Editor: More Data / ZoomType"

Command: @{b}More Data / ZoomType@{ub}

Message zoom type. Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_XferProt "Internal User Editor: More Data / XferProt"

Command: @{b}More Data / XferProt@{ub}

Shows the user's default transfer protocol.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_FirstCall "Internal User Editor: More Data / FirstCall"

Command: @{b}More Data / FirstCall@{ub}

Shows date & time of the user's first call.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_LastTime "Internal User Editor: More Data / LastTime"

Command: @{b}More Data / LastTime@{ub}

Shows date & time of the user's last call.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_Ansi "Internal User Editor: More Data / Ansi"

Command: @{b}More Data / Ansi@{ub}

Specifies if the user is having ANSI colours turned on or off.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_Hidden "Internal User Editor: More Data / Hidden"

Command: @{b}More Data / Hidden@{ub}

This is the user's current @{b}hidden@{ub} status, used if he/she doesn't want
others to recognize that he/she is online. Useful for FAME developers who
are going to call a FAME support site. :^)

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_FileClS "Internal User Editor: More Data / FileClS"

Command: @{b}More Data / FileClS@{ub}

States if the user wants to receive screen clear codes between pages when
viewing file listings.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_MsgClS "Internal User Editor: More Data / MsgClS"

Command: @{b}More Data / MsgClS@{ub}

States if the user wants to receive screen clear codes between pages when
reading messages.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_DefUpl "Internal User Editor: More Data / DefUpl"

Command: @{b}More Data / DefUpl@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_DefView "Internal User Editor: More Data / DefView"

Command: @{b}More Data / DefView@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_FileID "Internal User Editor: More Data / FileID"

Command: @{b}More Data / FileID@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_UserFBPW "Internal User Editor: More Data / UserFBPW"

Command: @{b}More Data / UserFBPW@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_MsgCryPW "Internal User Editor: More Data / MsgCryPW"

Command: @{b}More Data / MsgCryPW@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_LowCPSD "Internal User Editor: More Data / LowCPSD"

Command: @{b}More Data / LowCPSD@{ub}

Shows the user's lowest CPS rate he/she had somewhen.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_FileNuke "Internal User Editor: More Data / FileNuke"

Command: @{b}More Data / FileNuke@{ub}

Shows the number of files he/she got nuked by a file SysOp / Co-SysOp.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_GoodBye "Internal User Editor: More Data / GoodBye"

Command: @{b}More Data / GoodBye@{ub}

States if the user prefers a @{b}Normal@{ub} (default) or @{b}Fast@{ub} logoff
procedure. @{b}Fast@{ub} logoff means that FAME simply hangs up instead
of displaying any logoff texts.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_Extension "Internal User Editor: More Data / Extension"

Command: @{b}More Data / Extension@{ub}

Sets up the user's @{b}Screen Type@{ub} file extension for SysOp-defined
online text screens.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_Language "Internal User Editor: More Data / Language"

Command: @{b}More Data / Language@{ub}

Shows the user's preferred language which FAME and it's doors shall use.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_CompiType "Internal User Editor: More Data / CompiType"

Command: @{b}More Data / CompiType@{ub}

Specifies the user's computer type.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_ModemType "Internal User Editor: More Data / ModemType"

Command: @{b}More Data / ModemType@{ub}

Specifies the user's modem type.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_NewScan "Internal User Editor: More Data / NewScan"

Command: @{b}More Data / NewScan@{ub}

This is the user's new file/msg scan setup. It states if FAME shall scan
for files, messages, both, none or prompt for it when logging on.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_ExpertMode "Internal User Editor: More Data / ExpertMode"

Command: @{b}More Data / ExpertMode@{ub}

States if the user has @{b}Expert Mode@{ub} turned on or off. In the expert mode,
the online menus are suppressed. After a command was executed, FAME directly
falls back to the @{b}Main Prompt@{ub} instead of displaying the command menu.
After a user has learned all needed commands, switching off the help menus
speeds up BBS snooparound.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_StringEdit "Internal User Editor: More Data / StringEdit"

Command: @{b}More Data / StringEdit@{ub}

The days when this option has been called a "real feature" are numbered.
However, this option turns the FAME internal string edit function on,
where a user may use all supported features (cursor keys etc.), instead
of having the backspace key as only edit control.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_MsgRooming "Internal User Editor: More Data / MsgRooming"

Command: @{b}More Data / MsgRooming@{ub}

Specifies if you wish that the text/message LineEditor shall work in auto-
indent mode.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_DefDownl "Internal User Editor: More Data / DefDownl"

Command: @{b}More Data / DefDownl@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_DefZippy "Internal User Editor: More Data / Def.Zippy"

Command: @{b}More Data / Def.Zippy@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_Editor "Internal User Editor: More Data / Editor"

Command: @{b}More Data / Editor@{ub}

Selects the user's preferred text/message editor type.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_UserFileBase "Internal User Editor: More Data / UserFileBase"

Command: @{b}More Data / UserFileBase@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_DoMsgCrypt "Internal User Editor: More Data / DoMsgCrypt"

Command: @{b}More Data / DoMsgCrypt@{ub}

Not implemented yet.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_LowCPSUp "Internal User Editor: More Data / LowCPSUp"

Command: @{b}More Data / LowCPSUp@{ub}

This is the lowest upload CPS rate the user had somewhen.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_BytesNuked "Internal User Editor: More Data / BytesNuked"

Command: @{b}More Data / BytesNuked@{ub}

Shows the amount of bytes he/she got nuked by a file SysOp / Co-SysOp.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_MD_ASCIIMsg "Internal User Editor: More Data / ASCIIMsg"

Command: @{b}More Data / ASCIIMsg@{ub}

States if the user prefers the @{b}ASCIIMsg@{ub} mode used by the internal
Line Editor.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Presets "Internal User Editor: Presets"

Command: @{b}Presets@{ub}

The numeric hotkeys from 0 to 9 may be used to fill the current user account
with one of your SysOp defined user presets. Please refer to the System
Editor manual for more details.

@endnode

==============================================================================

@node InUsEd_Conferences "Internal User Editor: Conferences"

Command: @{b}Conferences@{ub}

This command invokes another conference-related user setup editor, where
you may specify many things for every single conference different to the
global user setup. All conference-related changes override the global
parameters.

     @{"   Username    :" link InUsEd_CF_Username}                             @{"   Usernumber  :" link InUsEd_CF_Usernumber}
     @{"(A)CnfUsername>:" link InUsEd_CF_CnfUsername}                             @{"(C)UserCnfXS  >:" link InUsEd_CF_UserCnfXS}
     @{"(D)SentLine   >:" link InUsEd_CF_SentLine}
     @{"(E)Ratio      >:" link InUsEd_CF_Ratio}                             @{"(F)RatioType  >:" link InUsEd_CF_RatioType}
     @{"(G)Conf Joins >:" link InUsEd_CF_ConfJoins}                             @{"(H)Zoom       >:" link InUsEd_CF_Zoom}
     @{"(I)Uploads    >:" link InUsEd_CF_Uploads}                             @{"(J)Downloads  >:" link InUsEd_CF_Downloads}
     @{"(K)BytesUpload>:" link InUsEd_CF_BytesUpload}                             @{"(L)BytesDownl.>:" link InUsEd_CF_BytesDownl}
     @{"(M)D.ByteLimit>:" link InUsEd_CF_DByteLimit}                             @{"(N)D.FileLimit>:" link InUsEd_CF_DFileLimit}
     @{"(O)D.ByteBonus>:" link InUsEd_CF_DByteBonus}                             @{"(P)D.FileBonus>:" link InUsEd_CF_DFileBonus}
     @{"(Q)D.ByteDl   >:" link InUsEd_CF_DByteDL}                             @{"(R)D.FileDl   >:" link InUsEd_CF_DFileDl}
     @{"(T)MsgWrite   >:" link InUsEd_CF_MsgWrite}                             @{"(U)MessageRead>:" link InUsEd_CF_MessageRead}
     @{"(V)MsgRead    >:" link InUsEd_CF_MsgRead}                             @{"(W)EMsgRead   >:" link InUsEd_CF_EMsgRead}
