@REM==============================================================================

@node "MCI-Commands" "MCI-Commands"

                                @{b}MCI Description
                               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

 - MCI commands are control sequences which will be replaced by variable text.
 - MCI commands can be placed in any text files.
 - MCI commands can be used by SysOp defined prompts like the 'pause prompt'.
 - MCI commands can be used by the user defined 'menu prompt'.
 - MCI commands can be used by Doors.

Note: All MCI command chars can be written shifted or unshifted means
      'A' can also be written as 'a'.


@{b}@{u}MCI introducer:@{ub}@{uu}
                ~ is the MCI introducer and must be at the beginning of
                any text file as the really first char.
                MCI interpretation is only started on a textfile if
                ~ is the first char.
                You can let this first ~ alone or you can use it as the
                first MCI command too. Maybe for a clear screen begin your
                text with ~f .


@{b}@{u}MCI command terminator:@{ub}@{uu}
                        A space ' 'Āor | is the MCI command terminator.
                        Every with ~ introduced MCI command needs to
                        be ended with the MCI command terminator, normally
                        a space. Note that if you want to have a space
                        between an MCI command and another word, you have
                        to do two spaces. The first is the MCI command
                        terminator and the second is your visuable space
                        character. With ~CMT you can change the command
                        terminator | to another char.


                   @{b}Following a list of available MCI commands
                  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                           @{fg highlight}Text specific MCI commands@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

~0         Clear ANSI colors
~1         Set foreground color to white.
~2         Set foreground color to green.
~3         Set foreground color to yellow.
~4         Set foreground color to blue.
~5         Set foreground color to purple.
~6         Set foreground color to cyan.
~7         Set foreground color to red.
~B         Set foreground color to bold.
~U         Set foreground color to underline.
~I         Set foreground color to italic.
~BG0       Set background color to black.
~BG1       Set background color to white.
~BG2       Set background color to green.
~BG3       Set background color to yellow.
~BG4       Set background color to blue.
~BG5       Set background color to purple.
~BG6       Set background color to cyan.
~BG7       Set background color to red.
~T         Display the current time.
~D         Display the current date.
~H         Do a backs pace.
~F         Do a clear screen.
~R         Send a return (CR/LF, "\r\n" kombination).

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                           @{fg highlight}User specific MCI commands@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

~N         Display the current user name.
~UL        Display the current user location.
~UO        Display the current user origin.
~P         Display the current user password.
~PH        Display the current user phone.
~TC        Display the current user total user calls.
~LC        Display the current user last call to the system.
~MP        Display the current user message posted.
~MR        Display the current user message read.
~AL        Display the current user access level.
~SN        Display the current user slot number.
~CA        Display the current user conference access.
~BR        Display the current user baudRate.
~CO        Display the current user computer equipment.
~MO        Display the current user modem.
~TL        Display the current user initial time limit at logon in minutes.
~TR        Display the current user number of mins remaining today.
~BU        Display the current user bytes uploaded.
~BD        Display the current user bytes downloaded.
~FU        Display the current user files uploaded.
~FD        Display the current user files downloaded.
~DBL       Display the current user daily byte limit.
~DBU       Display the current user daily byte used.
~DBB       Display the current user daily byte bonus.
~DFL       Display the current user daily file limit.
~DFU       Display the current user daily file used.
~DFB       Display the current user daily file bonus.
~OD        Display the current user online since date.
~OT        Display the current user online since time.
~TS        Time left in seconds
~TM        Time left in minutes

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                          @{fg highlight}System specific MCI commands@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

~BN        BBS Name
~BO        BBS Origin
~BS        SysOp Name
~CL        Displays a list of avail conferences for the current user.
~LN        Display the current user logged on-node.
~AC        Types the actual conference.
~AN        Types the actual conferencenumber.
~SC        Total Systemcalls.
~KEY       Wait for any key pressed. Ctrl-C and Ctrl-L aktive.
~PROMPT    Prompt the User to press a key. Ctrl-C and Ctrl-L aktive.
~PAUSE     Pause with (Y/s/c/ns) Ctrl-C and Ctrl-L aktive.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                           @{fg highlight}Miscellaneous MCI commands@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

~CMT       Change MCI-Command-Tterminator.
           CMT| or CMT. or CMT} etc... means | or . or } is the new
           Terminator

~Wx        Wait x seconds. Max 10 seconds usable.
~Nx        Numlines where x is the number of numlines you would like
           to have.

~~         This indicates you wish the ~ symbol to be appear, you can
           have as many of them as you like after the first ~ to be
           displayed.
           Note: no ',' on this command.

~xN        Cursor to X-Position on Screen.
~yN        Cursor to Y-Position on Screen.

~SR_<File> Displays a text <File> with cycle (random files), it will cycle
           until no higer number can be found. At this case it will restart
           at 1. The files to be cycled must have a number like here:
           (x)-File.txt where (x) is the number (1 till 32767).
           I think 32767 (WORD) is enough?! 8)
           <File> is the full path of the textfile(s) without suffix.

~SL_<File> The same as ~SR_<File>, but the next lower level will be used
           too i.e. Bull<Level>.txt -> Bull50.txt .

~SF_<File> Displays a text <File> without any specifications.
           <File> *must* be the full path, including the suffix!

~CC_<Name> Tries to start a Door/InternalCMD with the name: <Name>.
           First it tries to start the door as a
           CONF<current conference>CMD and than as a BBSCMD.

           See @{"Doors" link "Doors"} for CMD types.

~CD_<Name> Tries to start a Door (no InternalCMD) with the name: <Name>.
           First it tries to start the door as a
           CONF<current conference>CMD and than as a BBSCMD.

           See @{"Doors" link "Doors"} for CMD types.

~CI_<Name> Tries to start a InternalCMD (no Door) with the name: <Name>.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Arexx" "Arexx"

                                     @{b}Arexx
                                    ~~~~~~~@{ub}

The arexx port of the @{"MainPart" link "InternModules"} is not really implemented yet.
It knows only some commands.

Arexx port name: 'FAMERexxPort.<x>' where <x> stands for the Node number.

        Example: FAMERexxPort.0 is the arexx port of Node 0.


                               @{b}Available commands
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

@{b}@{u}Simple commands: (No arguments)@{ub}@{uu}

 - shutdown : Shut down the node with comment to a online user and a timeout.

              Usage: 'shutdown'

              Note: 'shutdown' is not tested and could be buggy.

 - suspend  : The Node releases the serial driver till it 'resume' receives.
              Used for scripts suspending the Node and starting a terminal
              instead.

              Usage: 'suspend'

 - resume   : The Node re-opens the serial driver closed by 'suspend'.

              Usage: 'resume'


@{b}@{u}Argument commands: (with arguments)@{ub}@{uu}

 - chat     : If the Node is in the SysOp chat mode this command is able to
              write a string into the chat which would look like:
              'REXX>: Arexx is speaking here!'

              Usage: 'chat Hallo, i'm transmitted via arexx!'

 - FAMESAY  : Write a text into the Node.

              Usage: 'FAMESAY Hello!'

 - FAMESAYLN: Write a text into the Node with linefeed.

              Usage: 'FAMESAYLN Hello!'

 - GETDATA  : Get datas from the Node.

              Usage: 'GETDATA <command>'

              Example: 'GETDATA 0'

              Note: There is only one command available yet:

              Commands: 0 - Get the chat flag state.

                        Result: 'ON' or 'OFF'.

              Note: Results are located in 'rm_Result2' of struct RexxMsg.


@{b}@{u}Example scripts@{ub}@{uu}

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* Shut down Node 0 */

interpret "address 'FAMERexxPort.0' shutdown"

exit
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* Write a text into the SysOp chat on Node 0 */

interpret "address 'FAMERexxPort.0' chat Hello! I am arexx!"
interpret "address 'FAMERexxPort.0' chat"

exit
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* Write a text with linefeed on Node 0 */

interpret "address 'FAMERexxPort.0' FAMESAYLN I am arexx!"

exit
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* Write a text without linefeed on Node 1 */

interpret "address 'FAMERexxPort.1' FAMESAY Hey hey ArexxMessage!!!"

exit
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* Suspend Node 0 */

interpret "address 'FAMERexxPort.0' suspend"

exit
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
/* Resume Node 0 */

interpret "address 'FAMERexxPort.0' resume"

exit
----------------------------------------------------------------------------


@{b}@{u}Example usage@{ub}@{uu}

Following a dos script to suspend a Node and start 'term' synchronousely
instead. After quitting 'term' the Node will be go online again.

For this you need to put both scripts above for suspending and resuming a
Node into two files named 'FAMEOFF.rexx' and 'FAMEON.rexx'. Copy them into
your (assigned) 'Rexx:' directory.

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
rx FAMEOFF.rexx  ;Call suspend.
stack 16384      ;Set the stack needed by 'term'.
TERM:TERM sync   ;Start term synchronousely.
rx FAMEON.rexx   ;Call resume.
----------------------------------------------------------------------------

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Programlogic" "Programlogic"

                              @{b}Programlogic of FAME
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Now we will show you what FAME (@{"MainPart" link "InternModules"}) internally does.
This will explain the programlogic and is a walkthrough through the BBS.
This will also help the SysOp about to understand what the Node does if
someone is logging on.
You will see where and when what kind of file will be shown, where and on
what case a prompt appears and when which @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} will be started.

We are beginning at the main screen, the 'Await-Screen' of the Node (@{"MainPart" link "InternModules"}).

As you can see there are 20 buttons equal to the F-Keys (function keys)
on your keyboard including the shifted ones (press shift and the F-key at the
same time). On the left side are the unshifted F-keys located and on the right
side are the shifted F-keys.

Here you can perform several actions like logins, starting the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}
or @{"UserEditor" link "InternModules"}, reserve for a user, edit a user and so on.

You can now use the gadgets or equal the F-keys to start an operation, but
there are some additional ways to perform the same actions.

First there are the gadgets on the Node screen, next the F-Keys
(shifted/unshifted), there are menus in the screen title, those menus
have shortcuts and last but not least there is the way to control all this
with the @{"Server" link "InternModules"}.


Next part is the walkthrough on connecting to the Node.


-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                     @{fg highlight}Walkthrough from the login procedure on@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

We now start a walkthrough from connecting on. We use this login way, because
this shows all possibilities on connecting till reaching the menu prompt.

If the Await-Screen of a Node appears the Node is ready to receive calls
from serial or to react on console actions. Only if the modem initializing
window appears the Node is busy for a short time, but iconifying the Node is
possible.

Below a list of signals a Node has to wait for:

 - Gadgets and menuitem selections of the screen (main window/backdrop window)

 - Console input like F-keys and other keys pressed on the sysop side.

 - Serial input like a RING if a user calls.

 - The closegadget at the top-left of the screen. This is an asynchron working
   window to place the closegadget at this position.

 - If the 'Iconify?' (Iconify Ask Window) is open. All actions to it will be
   watched. This window works also asynchron.

 - If the 'Status & Commands' (Status CMD Window), called by pressing 'Help',
   is open. All actions to it will be watched. This window works also
   asynchron.

 - Arexxport to check for possible commands from the Arexxport like 'suspend'
   and 'resume'.

 - ServerPort to check for incoming commands from the @{"Server" link "InternModules"}.

Later if a user is online this list of signals will raise a lot.


We now will see what happens if someone calls the BBS:

 - If the Node detects a RING it sends 'ATA' or the sysop defined answer
   string to the modem what means the modem should build up a connect now.

 - Next the Node checks the serial input stream for a 'CONNECT ...' string.
   Meanwhile a next signal will be checked, the timeout to break the
   modem connect try if it takes longer than 30 seconds where we can
   assume that an error exists. The Node also checks for a 'NO CARRIER'
   string and if it appears the connect procedure will also be canceled.
   If a 'NO CARRIER' or timeout is detected the Node resets itself and
   changes back to the Await-Mode, but if we now receive a 'CONNECT ...'
   string this string will be checked for some atributes in it, because the
   string contains more information like the connect rate of the connection.

 - The baud rate is now used for checking if the user is allowed to connect
   to the BBS with the actual baud rate. The SysOp can set those connect times
   in the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/Node Edit/mORE... under Baud Start/Endtimes.
   If the calling user isn't allowed to connect now, the Node displays a text
   file named: '<Screenslocation>:NoCallersAt<baud rate>' if it exists.
   If it doesn't exists a standard text will be displayed by the Node.

 - After this check is successful for the user the Node displays the
   connect string to the user, so the user is able to validate it.

 - Now the BBS displays the welcome message to the user which shows 
   information about the BBS, like FAME Version, Registration, BBS name and
   Location and many more...

 - The Node checks for a @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'FRONTEND', if it can be found the BBS
   starts the according Interface Module, normally a door. If this @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"}
   can't be found the Node displays the Node internal front status of the BBS
   if the SysOp want to have it.

 - The Node checks for a @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'ANSI', if it can be found the BBS
   starts the according Interface Module, normally a door.
   If this @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} can'tĀbe found the Node displays its own ansi prompt where
   the user can choose between the following possibilities:

   - I means ignore and use user settings.
   - y means yes, ANSI graphics on.
   - n means no, ANSI graphics off.
   - r means use RIP graphics.
   - @ means a netcall is coming in (not usable by an user).

 - If the SysOp has defined a System Password in the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/Node Edit
   under 'System Password' and he also has defined a value higher 0 in the
   field 'Max SysPW Failure' in the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/System Datas the Node
   now checks for a @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'SYSPW', if it can be found the BBS starts
   the according Interface Module, normally a door. If this @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} can't be
   found the Node looks for a text file named: '<Screenslocation>:Private.txt'
   which will be displayed to the user.

   Now the Node prompts for the System Password.
   The user has as much times left to type the correct System Password as the
   SysOp has configured in the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/System Datas under
   'Max SysPW Failure'.

   If the user fails with typing the correct System Password the Node drops
   the carrier. The Node also writes the false entries to the Callers.log
   file in the Node.

 - If a text file named: '<Screenslocation>:Title.txt> is found it will be
   displayed to the user.

 - Now the Node shows the user name prompt where the user must enter the user
   name where Wildcards are allowed.

   The only used Wildcard is the asterisk '*'.

   The user name: 'UserName' can be written shorter: 'User*' or 'U*'.

   You must enter 1 char as a minimum with the asterisk '*'.

   If more than one username matches the user can skip trough them to find
   the right user name.

   Another way to login is via the user slot number, on condition the user
   knows it.
   '1' for example is the user with the slotnumber 1, which is the SysOp.

   The user has as many tries left as the SysOp wants to.
   Set it with the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} under System Datas/Max UserPW Failure.
   If the user overrides this value the Node drops the carrier.

 - After entering the user name there are two ways. First the user name exists
   then the Node continues with the user password. If the user name doesn't
   exist the Node will ask for a new user entry if the SysOp hasn't disabled
   the new user function under @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/Node Edit/mORE.../NewUser.

 - The Node now asks if the user will retry his name entry for the case he
   did an error before. The other choice is to continue as new user.


Because of those two now following different ways a user can go, we are
now explaining first the way of a new user and then we continue with the
normal way a valid user goes. They will be from that point again the same.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                                 @{fg highlight}New User Entry@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

 - If the user is the first user in the BBS he will become the SysOp.
   Note this! Else the BBS welcomes you as a normal new user.

 - If the SysOp has set a NewUserPassword, the Node now asks the user for
   this password, in this case the following happens:

   - The Node checks for a @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'NUP', if it can be found the
     BBS starts the according Interface Module, normally a door. If no 'NUP'
     can be found the Node displays the '<Screenslocation>:NewUserPW.txt>
     to the user.

   - The new user prompt prompts for the new user password.

     The user has Max NUP Failure times to type the NUP correctly.
     If the user fails, the Node drops the carrier and resets the Node.
     On every wrong entry the Node writes the wrong password to the
     Callers.log like on every password prompt.

   - The Node will look before it kicks the user out of the BBS for a
     @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'NUPFAIL', if it can be found the BBS starts the according
     Interface Module, normally a door.

 - After the New User Password procedure the above told welcome message
   appears.

 - Now it's time for the new user entry.

   The Node asks for the following diffenrent things.

   Note: If you want back to a prompt before just clear the current input
   (delete all chars) and hit return. Now you come one step back... you
   can do the same here, till you reach the first question.

   For example you have entered your phone number and you see that your
   user name is written wrong you have to delete the phone number and hit
   return. Now you do the same if the user name prompt appears. Edit your
   name and hit anter. As you can see nothing of your previous written
   answers are lost, they will all appear till your last entered prompt.
   Just hit return as long as you reach your last answered prompt.

 - Next prompts have a limit of errors (endless return pressings).
   Find this under @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/System Datas/Max Name Failure.

 - First you will be asked for your user name you want to use in this BBS.
   Choose a name you really want to have for a longer time.
   As you can see the Node will show you the name you have already typed,
   edit it now or use the name.

   If the user name includes wildcards, belongs of numeric digits only or
   is shorter than 3 chars the Node informs the user about this, that this
   is not allowed and displays the name prompt again.

 - Next step is the Node checks for user names not allowed in the BBS
   and uses a list of names given in: '<BBSLocation:>NamesNotAllowed.txt'.
   If one of these names matches with the user's one the Node notifies it
   to the user and asks again for the name.

   Note: You should specify SYSOP, ALL, EALL and UEALL in that list.

 - Now the Node checks for duplicate names, if your name already exists
   the Node asks again for the username.

 - The Node asks now for the following things:

   - users personal password.

   - users location. Maybe a group name.

   - users origin (city/state).

   - users phone number.

   - users number of lines on screen (1-100).

   - users computer type.

   - users modem type.

   - users suffix type, means text language settings.

   - users BBS language.

   - if the new user wants to have clear screens on messages.

   - if the new user wants to have clear screens on file lists.

 - The Node asks for the red/white swap to have correct red and white colors.
   If red and white shall be swaped all strings which will be send to serial
   will be converted in the colors [31m to [37m and [37m to [31m .

 - Finally the Node aks if all settings are correct.

   The Node lists all the settings the new user has made.

   If the new user types here no, the user will be back at the username
   prompt, but all previous made settings will be left intact so that a
   single answer can be edited and not everything must be answered again.

 - The Node checks for a @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'NEWUSER', if it can be found the
   BBS starts the according Interface Module, normally a door.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                            @{fg highlight}Normal users procedures@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

 - If the SysOp wants the Node to check if the user is already logged with
   this name to another Node (@{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/System Datas/MultiNodeUser).
   If it's so the Node notifies this in the Callers.log and to the user and
   drops the carrier.

 - The Node now checks if the Node is reserved for a specially single user.
   If it's so the Node notifies the user about that with a text file called
   '<Screenslocation:>ReservedForUser.txt' and drops the carrier.

 - The Node now prompts for the users password.
   The user has @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}/System Datas/Max UserPW Failure times to enter
   it correctly, if the user fails the Node drops the carrier.
   On every failure the Node writes the wrong password into in the
   Callers.log.

 - If the password fails the Node checks before it drops the carrier for a
   @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'PWFAIL', if it can be found the BBS starts the according
   Interface Module, normally a door.
   'PWFAIL' is normally used by password fail doors which let those users
   write a mail to the SysOp.


From now on the two different ways will come together.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
                             @{fg highlight}Walktrough continuing@{fg text}
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

 - The Node starts now all LogonBatches.

 - The Node checks if the user should be captured.

 - Logon.txt

 - ...

 - The Node checks for a @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} named 'LATEANSI', if it can be found the
   BBS starts the according Interface Module, normally a door. If not a
   second 'ANSI Graphics?' prompt appears, but only if the user settings are
   set to this and the first ANIS prompt was answered with 'Ignore'.
   If this @{"SYSCMD" link "Doors"} can'tĀbe found the Node will show its own late ansi
   prompt, but only if the SysOp has disabled the early and first ansi prompt
   and the user settings forces to bring this prompt. In this way the user
   can decide whether this prompt shall appear or not.

 - ...

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "F-keys" "F-keys"

             @{b}This is the F-key definition if the Node awaits a call
            ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F1  - SysOp login.
Shift + F1  - Fast SysOp login.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F2  - Local login.
Shift + F2  - Fast local login.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F3  - Remote Login.
Shift + F3  - Fast remote login.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F4  - Reserve for a user.
Shift + F4  - For future use.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F5  - Conference access editor.
Shift + F5  - Start the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F6  - Internal UserEditor.
Shift + F6  - External module @{"UserEditor" link "InternModules"}.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F7  - Chat Toggle.
Shift + F7  - For future use.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F8  - Initialize Modem.
Shift + F8  - For future use.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F9  - Exit Node.
Shift + F9  - For future use.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F10 - Exit Node off hook.
Shift + F10 - Iconify Node.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------


                @{b}This is the F-key definition if a user is online
               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F1  - Chat in/out with StartChat.txt .
Shift + F1  - Chat in/out with StartChat2.txt .

Note: Shift + F1 or F1 again leaves chat with EndChat.txt or EndChat2.txt .
      This depends on the used StartChat<x>.txt .
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F2  - Increase online users time limit +10 mins.
Shift + F2  - Can be used by doors.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F3  - Decrease online users time limit -10 mins.
Shift + F3  - Can be used by doors.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F4  - Capturing users activities on/off.
Shift + F4  - Pop up an ASL Requester to let you choose an ASCII File to be
              shown.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F5  - Local Shell.
Shift + F5  - Pop up an ASL Requester to let you choose an File to be send.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F6  - Account Editing.
Shift + F6  - SysopXS Account Editing.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F7  - Chat flag toggle.
Shift + F7  - Reserved.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F8  - Serial in on/off.
Shift + F8  - Reserved.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F9  - Serial out on/off.
Shift + F9  - Reserved.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
        F10 - Kick User, Logoff.
Shift + F10 - Kick User, Logoff + Exit Node.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "FAMEModules" "FAME Modules"

                                  @{b}FAME Modules
                                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

                         @{u}There are two types of Modules@{uu}

                               @{" Internal Modules " link "InternModules"}
                               @{" External Modules " link "ExternModules"}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Batches" "How to use and install scripts for FAME"

                               @{b}FAME Batch scripts
                              ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

FAME supports four different types of batch scripts. These are:

          START   - Will be executed when starting a Node

          END     - Will be executed when a Node will be finished

          LOGON   - Will be executed on user's logon

          LOGOFF  - Will be executed after user's logoff


This scripts will be used to start external tools like LastCallers or
Multi-Top. As this tools are CLI-tools and no Doors, you have to start them
from these batches. FAME uses the following way to execute scripts:

FAME checks if you have set a batch file for a Node in the Node Datas of
the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"}. If found, the script will be executed. This allows you to
give every Node his own special batchscript. The better way of using scripts
is to use the according script-directories which will be found in directory
@{fg fill}FAME:Node<x>/NodeBatches/@{fg text}. Here you'll find four directories, each of them
represents one of the Batchtypes explained above. To built in a script into
one of the directories, all you have to do is writing the script and coping
it to the according NodeBatches/ directory! FAME searches in these dirs for
scripts and if found, executes them file by file. This makes it very easy
for you to add or remove new scripts, simply copy/delete them to/from the
according NodeBatches/ directory. Also the Nodenumber will be given as 
argument when executing scripts, so it's easy to pass the Nodenumber to the
tools. Here's an example for a Logoff-Batchscript, which will start the
LastCallers util shipped with the FAME-Release:

@{b}--- CUT HERE ---@{ub}

.key node
.bra <
.ket >

C:LASTCALLERS FAME:NODE<node>/CALLERS.LOG <node> 10 FAME:LASTCALLERS.TXT

@{b}--- CUT HERE ---@{ub}

This starts the LastCallers with the Node argument, so LastCallers is able
to access the right callerslog of the Node which executes the script. As
you could see, it's very easy to install scripts.

@{u}NOTE:@{uu} Make sure that you've set the protection-bit '@{b}s@{ub}' for all your scripts,
      or FAME won't be able to execute them!! Use the following command to
      set this bit: '@{fg fill}PROTECT <scriptname> +s@{fg text}'. This enables the ADOS feature
      of executing textfiles just with their filename instead of using the
      DOS-Command Execute.

It would also be possible to copy executables into the NodeBatch directories.
They will be executed too with the Nodenumber as argument.

Normally, scriptfiles where executed in file-by-file order, meaning that
the next script will be executed when the current script is done. If you
have a Multi-Node board and two users i.e. logs off from your BBS at once,
one of the Nodes must wait until the first Node is done with the logoff-
scripts. If you have i.e. many logoff scripts at once, it may take very 
long until all Nodes are ready for the next callers. To avoid this, set for
the according Nodes the flag '@{fg fill}ASYNCHRONOUS ...BATCHES@{fg text}'  for every batchtype
you've want to change (See SystemEditor/NodeEdit/More NodeEdit/ ).
In @{b}ASYNCHRON@{ub} mode all Nodescripts where executed when it's needed, i.e. if
two users are exiting your BBS at the same time, both logoff-scripts will 
also be executed at the same time. This saves time for the Logoff-Procedure
but to use this, the tools you are using inside your scripts @{b}MUST@{ub} support
these feature!! Imagine the LastCallers util shipped with FAME, if you run
this tool in @{b}ASYNCHRON@{ub} mode, many problems could occure, as it uses one
datafile for @{u}ALL Nodes@{uu}, and if two programs are trying to change the same
datafile at the same time, it won't work. So check out the documentations
of the tools you want to use if they are able to support this feature. If
you are not sure, @{b}DON'T USE IT!@{ub}

The @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} settings could be overriden by using the Filecomments
@{fg fill}SYNCHRON@{fg text} or @{fg fill}ASYNCHRON@{fg text}. If you have set i.e. the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} setting to
ASYNCHRON, but you have a tool which doesn't support this, set the file
comment of the script from where you started your door to SYNCHRON. FAME
will then execute this script with waiting on other Nodes, but all other
scripts will be executed just when they where started.

@endnode

