@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "MsgBase" "Message Base and LineEd description"

                      @{b}Message Base and LineEd description
                     ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

                            @{" Read/Reply a Message  " link "ReadMessageCmds"}
                            @{"    Write a Message    " link "WriteMessage"}
                            @{"      Line Editor      " link "LineEditor"}
                            @{"    Message Header     " link "MessageHeader"}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "ReadMessageCmds" "Read/Reply a Message"

                              @{b}Read/Reply a Message
                             ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

If you read a message with the menu command 'R' and a message is available
in the way you read you will see first a @{"Message Header" link "MessageHeader"} and than
you will see the message itself.


@{b}@{u}Mail pause prompt@{ub}@{uu}

After a screen is full with text you will get a prompt which will look like:

Pause, more? (Y)es,(N)onstop,(C)lear,(R)eply,(Q)uit>:

 - (Y)es       : Is the same as you hit Enter/Return, the mail text continues
                 to scroll (prompt disappears).

 - (N)onstop   : This will no longer brings this pause prompt we describe
                 here for the current mail. Break it with Ctrl-C.

 - (C)lear     : The same as you hit Enter/Return or (Y)es, except the whole
                 mail no longer scrolls, because a clear screen will be made.

 - (R)eply     : To fast reply from every pause prompt the current mail.
                 Normally used if you really know what this mail is about
                 and you want reply it for sure.

                 Note: The user settings 'MESSAGE QUOTE', 'PRIVATE ON REPLY'
                       and 'MSG SUBJECT ON REPLY' will be used if you reply
                       here!

 - (Q)uit      : To quit the current mail.

 - Enter/Return: Exactly the same as (Y)es.

The pause prompt only reacts on this above described key pressings other
keys will be ignored.


@{b}@{u}Control keys on viewing a mail@{ub}@{uu}

While a mail will be viewd you can also use two Ctrl keys which can be
everywhere used if text will be viewed in FAME:

 - Ctrl-C: To break the view.

 - Ctrl-L: To do a clear screen.


@{b}@{u}Read Message Prompt@{ub}@{uu}

If the mail has been completely viewed you will reach the Read Msg Options
prompt we now describe.

There are two different types of this prompt, first the message read prompt
if you type 'R' in the menu and second the message scan prompt if you login
and the new message scanner appears or you enter 'ms' in the menu:

Read Msg Options: A,D,E,K,O,R,S,N,Q,NS,+,-,? (Enter->Next/110+159) >:
                  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^  ^^^^^^^^^^^ ^^^ ^^^
                             a)                    b)      c)  d)

Msg Scan Options: A,D,K,O,R,Q,NS,? (Enter->Next/157+159) >:
                  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^  ^^^^^^^^^^^ ^^^ ^^^
                         a)              b)      c)  d)

a) Possible options:

 - A : Again.

       Display the current mail again.

 - D : Delete.

       Delete the current message.

       Note: Only possible if the mail is from or to you or you have the
             level to delete foreign mail.

 - E : Edit.

       Edit the current message.

       Note: Only possible if the mail is from you or you have the
             level to edit foreign mail.

       Note: Not possible on message scan mode.

 - K : Keep.

       Kepp the current message for a later time.

       Note: Only possible if the mail is from or to you or you have the
             level to keep foreign mail.

 - O : Other User.

       Divert the current message to a other user.

       Note: Only possible if the mail is from or to you or you have the
             level to divert foreign mail to a other user.

 - R : Reply.

       Reply to the current message.

       Note: The user settings 'MESSAGE QUOTE', 'PRIVATE ON REPLY'
             and 'MSG SUBJECT ON REPLY' will be used if you reply
             with command 'R'!

 - S : Set Message Pointer

       You can set your message pointer for the 'R' read mail command
       we describe here.

       Note: Not possible on message scan mode.

 - N : Set NewScan Message Pointer

       You can set your NewScan message pointer for the new mail scanner
       or the 'ms' command.

       Note: Not possible on message scan mode.

 - Q : Quit.

       You can quit the message reader.

 - + : Positive direction.

       If you already read in the positive (Next) direction it will just
       display the next mail, else it would change the direction to
       forward mail read.

       Note: Not possible on message scan mode.

 - - : Negative direction.

       If you already read in the negative (Previous) direction it will
       just display the previous mail, else it would change the direction
       to backward mail read.

       Note: Not possible on message scan mode.

 - ? : Help.

       Displays a short command help.

 - NS: Non stop.

       To read mails non stop.

       This will no longer brings the pause prompt if a mail is longer
       as you have lines and it also displays all other comming mails
       you would read if you would hit return after each readen mail.
       It continues displaying all messages without stoping, except
       a file is attached on a mail or you break it with Ctrl-C.
       Of course you can also use Ctrl-L for a clear screen.

 - RP: Reply Msg with prompting.

       'RP' is because of the fact that 'R' uses your default user settings
       'MESSAGE QUOTE', 'PRIVATE ON REPLY' and 'MSG SUBJECT ON REPLY'.

       With 'RP' you will be prompted for new subject, private flag and
       message quote.

 - RN: Reply Msg without prompting.

       'RN' is because of the fact that 'R' uses your default user settings
       'MESSAGE QUOTE', 'PRIVATE ON REPLY' and 'MSG SUBJECT ON REPLY'.

       With 'RN' you will *NOT* be prompted for new subject, private flag
       and message quote.


b) Next or previous mail will be viewed on pressing Enter/Return.

   Note: On message scan there is only the previous mail direction possible!

c) Next or previous mail number.

   Note: The real next/previous mail mustn't be exactly the same number as
         displayed here, because there can be some deleted mails.

   Note: On message scan there is only the next mail direction possible!
         In this case there is no previous mail number available and you
         can't use '-'.

d) Last/first mail number.

   The number displayed here depends on the direction you read mail.


@{b}@{u}More@{ub}@{uu}

For more information see the 'R' menu command description.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "WriteReply" "Write a Message"

                                @{b}Write a Message
                               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

To write a mail please see the description of the 'W' menu command
and how to use the @{"LineEditor" link "LineEditor"}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "LineEditor" "Line Editor"

                                  @{b}Line Editor
                                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

@{b}@{u}In the Line Editor@{ub}@{uu}

The Line Editor has two different modes:

 - Normal mode: To write/reply normal mails.

 - Ascii Mode : To write/reply normal mails, edit other files, snap/send
                text into.

                In the 'Ascii Mode' 'Message Rooming', 'line counter' and
                'jump to editor prompt on empty lines + return' is off.

Which mode you use depends on your user settings. Change the mode with
the 'W' menu command. You can also change everytime in the Line Editor
between both modes, except the Line Editor is used for external files.

If you are in the 'Ascii Mode' you can only use commands with the Ctrl
key codes. They are explained below.

If you are in the 'Normal mode' you can use commands with the Ctrl key codes
or directly from the command prompt. To jump into the command prompt you
simply have to leave the last line blank (no chars in it) and hit return
or you use the depending Ctrl key code (see below) to jump into the
command prompt.


@{b}@{u}Message Rooming@{ub}@{uu}

'Message Rooming' is a feature you can everytime activate/deactivate
with the depending Ctrl key code (see below) or if you jump with an empty
line into the command prompt.

Message Rooming is a automatic space inserter.
If you have it active and you begin a line with more than one space
the Line Editor will automaticly fill the next lines up with the same
ammount of spaces for you.

Example:

1> This is normal: - I see!
2>                 - I was adding such spaces you can see left!
3>                 - Ohh! Nice, i musn't insert the spaces you can see left!
4>                 - Wow! Line Editor was inserting the spaces for me!


@{b}@{u}Line Editor command description@{ub}@{uu}

The Line Editor command line will look like:

Enter Msg Options: A,B,C,D,E,I,K,L,O,P,R,S,V,X,#,? >:

The commands are:

 - A: Abort Msg.

      Abort this message. All text will lost!

 - B: Begin ASCII Send.

      Change into the 'Ascii Mode'.

 - C: Continue Msg.

      Jump back to the last line of the mail.

 - D: Delete.

      Delete a specific line or a range of lines.

      You will see this prompt:

      Enter Lines to delete (1-<y>/*->ALL) >:

      Type here the number of one single line, a range of lines (<x>-<y>)
      or use '*' to delete all available lines.

      Hit return only to abort!

 - E: Edit.

      Edit a specific line.

      You will see this prompt:

      Enter Line to edit (1-<y>) >:

      Type here the number of the line you want to edit.

      Hit return only to abort!

      If you enter a valid number you will see this:

      Old Line
          [|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|-]
       <y>>Old text

      Enter New Line
          [|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|-]
       <y>>

      Here you can enter the new text for thie line <y>.

 - I: Insert.

      Insert a new line.

      You will see this prompt:

      Enter Line where to insert a new line (1-<y>) >:

      Type here the number of the line where you want to have a new line
      inserted.

      If you enter a valid number you will see this:

       [|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|-]
      3>

      Here you can enter the text for the new line inserted.

 - K: Crypt & Save Msg.

      Crypt and save the message.

      @{"Not implemented yet" link "NotImplemented"}

 - L: List.

      List the currently written text with line numbers.

 - O: Online Ctrl-Codes.

      Displays a short online control key code help.

      The online control key codes are:

        - Ctrl-A -> Abort, Goto MsgOptions (Command prompt).

        - Ctrl-B -> Begin, ASCII Send.

        - Ctrl-X -> Delete Line.

        - Ctrl-K -> Crypt and Save Message.

        - Ctrl-R -> Toggle 'Message Rooming' On/Off.

        - Ctrl-S -> Save Message.

 - P: Priority.

      Priority mails.

      @{"Not implemented yet" link "NotImplemented"}

 - R: Rooming.

      Toggle 'Message Rooming' On/Off.

 - S: Save.

      Save the message.

 - V: View.

      View the message without line numbers just like the receiver would
      see it.

 - X: Upload.

      Upload files to this message and save.

 - #: Auto delete.

      Days after this message will be automaticly deleted.

      @{"Not implemented yet" link "NotImplemented"}

 - ?: Help.

       Displays a short command help.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "MessageHeader" "Message Header"

                                 @{b}Message Header
                                ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

@{b}@{u}Description of the Mail Header contents@{ub}@{uu}

 - Date       : The date where the mail has been written.

 - Number     : The message number out of the Message Header data file.

   - Real     : The number of the displayed message (file read name).

 - To         : The name of the user the mail is for or:

                - ALL : Mail is public and for all users readable.
                        The new mail scanner won't display them.

                - EALL: Same as ALL but the new mail scanner will display
                        them too.

                - UELL: Same as EALL but level depending and for normal
                        users. Every single user will be able to set from
                        which level on he will receive such mail.
                        
                        @{"Not implemented yet" link "NotImplemented"}!

 - From       : The name of the user which has written the mail.

 - Subject    : The mesage subject. What this message is about.

 - Received   : - YES: The 'To' reader has received this mail.

                -  NO: The 'To' reader hasn't received this mail yet.

   - (Read: <x> times): How many time (other users also) this mail has been
                        readen.

 - Status     : - Private Message: Mail is private to the 'To' reader.

                - Public Message : Mail is public and for the 'To' reader.
                                   Everyone can read this mail too.

 - Files      : - Msg only!!       : This is a pure mail.

                - File(s) attached!: This mail has file(s) attached.

 - Crypt      : For mail crypting.

                @{"Not implemented yet" link "NotImplemented"}!

 - Del in Days: - Switched off!: No auto delete.

                - <x>          : Mail will be deleted in <x> days.

                @{"Not implemented yet" link "NotImplemented"}!

@endnode

