@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "InternModules" "Internal Modules"

                                @{b}Internal Modules
                               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

Internal Modules are executabled needed for FAME.

The most are a *must* to run FAME others are additional but depending
directly to FAME and most of them are a part of FAME selling package.


                    @{b}@{u}Following Internal Modules are available@{ub}@{uu}

   @{"      Server      " link "Server.guide/main"} - Controlling center of FAME.
   @{"     MainPart     " link "MainPart.guide/main"} - The Node of FAME.
   @{"   SystemEditor   " link "SystemEditor.guide/main"} - Config program for FAME.
   @{"    UserEditor    " link "UserEditor.guide/main"} - External user data editor.

                        @{b}For more information see @{"About" link "About"}.@{ub}

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "ExternModules"

                                @{b}External Modules
                               ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

   @{" FAMESwitchWindow " link "FAMESwitchWindow"} - Window switcher for MainPart.

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "Doors" "Doors"

                     @{b}Doors or Interface Modules under FAME
                    ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

@{b}@{u}There are three different ways of calling a door@{ub}@{uu}

    BBSCMD: - Commands started by typing the door call name into the menu
              prompt, called from another door or called from a @{"MCI Command" link "mci-commands"}.
CONF<x>CMD: - The same as BBSCMD, but conference depending where <x> is the
              conference number.
    SYSCMD: - SYSCMDs can't be started from users they will be started
              (if available) from @{"MainPart" link "InternModules"} in different phases.

              Example: 'FRONTEND' to replace the internal FRONTEND by a door.

                 Note: Some SYSCMDs can be started multiple door.
                       They will be marked with the <x> as a define for a
                       Node number.


@{b}@{u}Available SYSCMDs@{ub}@{uu}

ACCOUNTS    : - Replaces the Internal UserEditor.

                Argument will be:
                'ACCOUNTS USNUM:<UserNumber> USNAME:<UserName>'

ANSI        : - Replaces the ANSI prompt at the login procedure.

CHATIN<x>   : - Door(s) will be started on entering the sysop chat.

CHATOUT<x>  : - Door(s) will be started on leaving the sysop chat.
                In this case the door gets also the following arguments:

                1. The time chated in seconds.
                2. Number of chars typed by the sysop.
                3. Number of chars typed by the user.

                Template for ReadArgs will be:

                TIMECHATED/K/N/A,SYSOPCHARS/K/N/A,USERCHARS/K/N/A

                MainPart will build for example the following argument string:

                TIMECHATED=157 SYSOPCHARS=267 USERCHARS=235

CONFPWFAIL  : - Will be called if a user fails on entering the correct
                Conference security password.

DLSTAT      : - Calls a door after completed download procedure with an
                argument string full of information:

                'DLSTAT FILES=%ld BYTES=%ld CPS=%ld EFF=%ld MODE=%ld INT=%ld'

                %ld means a long value.
                EFF means efficiency.
                MODE see: FAMEDefine.h "UL/DLSTAT Mode defines"
                INT means 1 for Internal or local / 0 for remote or serial.

DLSTAT<x>   : - The same as 'DLSTAT', but for more different doors.

DOORHELP    : - Called by doors for the DoorHelp standard for doors.

                Argument will be: '<path+guide>'

DUPECHECK   : - The same as 'FILECHECK'.

                You should use 'DUPECHECK' and not 'FILECHECK' for dupe
                checkers! The reason is that in some cases a dupe checker
                shouldn't be started, like in overwrite mode of files.

                Note: For compatibility reasons the argument line for
                      'DUPECHECK' begins not with DUPECHECK, but with
                      'FILECHECK'.
                      This information is only useful for door programmer.

DUPECHECK<x>: - The same as 'FILECHECK<x>'.

                You should use 'DUPECHECK<x>' and not 'FILECHECK<x>' for dupe
                checkers! The reason is that in some cases a dupe checker
                shouldn't be started, like in overwrite mode of files.

                Note: For compatibility reasons the argument line for
                      'DUPECHECK<x>' begins not with DUPECHECK<x>, but with
                      'FILECHECK<x>'.
                      This information is only useful for door programmer.

EDITOR      : - The second possible external message editor as replacement
                for the internal line editor. The other is 'FULLED'.

ERROR       : - Calls the FAMEError.FIM door if an error occours.

                On error argument will be:
                '<ErrorNumber> 0 <ErrorCode> <AdditionalInfoNr>'

                On error which ends the Node argument will be:
                '0 <ErrorNumber> <UserNumber> <BackFlag> <WhereIAmPhase>'...
                ...' <WhatLogonPhase>' (continued string)

EXAMINE     : - Will be called after uploading files for every uploaded file
                which wasn't already posted by the external @{"FAMEFileChecker" link "FAMEFileChecker.guide/Main"}
                process.
                Normally used by file identify doors.
                If such a file identify door creates the description for the
                file successfully @{"MainPart" link "InternModules"} doesn't ask for the file
                description.

                Argument will be: 'EXAMINE <Path+FileName>'

EXAMINE<x>  : - The same as 'EXAMINE'.

                Argument will be: 'EXAMINE<x> <Path+FileName>'
                where <x> is a counter for more doorcalls.

FILECHECK   : - Will be called after uploading files for every uploaded file
                which wasn't already posted by the external @{"FAMEFileChecker" link "FAMEFileChecker.guide/Main"}
                process.
                Normally used by file checker doors.

                Argument will be: 'FILECHECK <FileName>'

FILECHECK<x>: - The same as 'FILECHECK'.

                Argument will be: 'FILECHECK<x> <FileName>'
                where <x> is a counter for more doorcalls.

FILEIDENT   : - The same as 'EXAMINE'.

                In future versions of FAME it can be that not in every
                case a FileId extractor will be needed. That's the reason
                why you should build in such extractors under 'FILEIDENT'
                and not under 'EXAMINE' !

                Note: For compatibility reasons the argument line for
                      'FILEIDENT' begins not with FILEIDENT, but with
                      'EXAMINE'.
                      This information is only useful for door programmer.

FILEIDENT<x>: - The same as 'EXAMINE<x>'.

                In future versions of FAME it can be that not in every
                case a FileId extractor will be needed. That's the reason
                why you should build in such extractors under 'FILEIDENT<x>'
                and not under 'EXAMINE<x>' !

                Note: For compatibility reasons the argument line for
                      'FILEIDENT<x>' begins not with FILEIDENT<x>, but with
                      'EXAMINE<x>'.
                      This information is only useful for door programmer.

FRONTEND    : - Replaces the internal FRONTEND by a door.

FULLED      : - The first possible external message editor as replacement
                for the internal line editor, normally the FAMEFullEd
                fullscreen editor.

LATEANSI    : - Replaces the late ANSI prompt at the login procedure.
                Appears after the user is valid (after password prompt) if
                the SysOp has turned of the earlier ANSI prompt and the user
                which to see the late ANSI prompt else user defined settings
                will be used.

LOGOFF      : - Will be started if a user has been logged off right before
                starting the logoff batches and after carrier drop and
                user data back writings.

LOGOFF<x>   : - The same as 'LOGOFF'.

MAILHEADER  : - Replaces the mail header which will be viewed on reading
                mail by a door.

MSGSCAN     : - Replaces the internal mail scan procedure by a door.

N           : - Replaces the newfile scan on message/file scan procedure
                by a door.

                Argument will be: 'N S U'

NEWUSER     : - Will be started right after a new user has completed the
                new user application.
                Normally used by new user question doors for more
                information about the user.

NUKED       : - Will be started if a Nuker has nuked bytes and files, but
                only if the Nuker supports the FIM commands 'NC_Nuked' or
                'NC_NukedAfter'.

                Doors called by this SYSCMD can get the following argument
                string on using the FIM command NR_MainLine:

                'NUKED NNFILES=%ld NNBYTES=%lu USERSLOT=%ld USERNAME=%s'...
                ...' UFILESU=%ld UBYTESU=%lu UFILESD=%ld UBYTESD=%lu'...
                ...' NFILES=%ld NBYTES=%lu' (continued string)

                Description:

                - NUKED         The SYSCMD name.

                - NNFILES=%ld   Nuked Files. Files nuked NOW.
                                (long value)

                - NNBYTES=%lu   Nuked Bytes. Bytes nuked NOW.
                                (unsigned long value)

                - USERSLOT=%ld  Nuked user's slot number.

                - USERNAME=%s   Nuked user's name.

                - UFILESU=%ld   Nuked user's uploaded files overall.
                                (long value)

                - UBYTESU=%lu   Nuked user's uploaded bytes overall.
                                (unsigned long value)

                - UFILESD=%ld   Nuked user's downloaded files overall.
                                (long value)

                - UBYTESD=%lu   Nuked user's downloaded bytes overall. 
                                (unsigned long value)

                - NFILES=%ld    Nuked user's nuked bytes overall.
                                (long value)

                - NBYTES=%lu"   Nuked user's nuked files overall.
                                (unsigned long value)

NUKED<x>    : - The same as 'NUKED', but for more different doors.

NUP         : - Replaces the new user password procedure if a new user
                password is needed to be allowed to do the new user
                application.

NUPFAIL     : - Will be started if the new user fails entering the new user
                password, directly before he will be droped.

                Argument will be: 'NUPFAIL <UserName>'

OWNDEVUNIT  : - Will be called if MainPart receives a request from the
                OwnDevUnit.library to give the currently used device + unit
                free.

                The door receives following arguments:

                1. The device currently used.
                2. The unit number of the device currently used.

                Template for ReadArgs will be:

                DEVICE/K/A,UNIT/K/N/A

                MainPart will build for example the following argument string:

                DEVICE="serial.device" UNIT=0

                Note: OWNDEVUNIT will only be called if a user is online
                      and the OwnDevUnit.library is used.

OWNDEVUNITA : - The same as OWNDEVUNIT, but will only be called if the Node
                is in "Await" mode.

                Note: OWNDEVUNIT will only be used if OwnDevUnit.library
                      is used.

PWFAIL      : - Will be started if the user fails entering the user password.
                Normally used by password fail doors which let those users
                write a mail to the SysOp.

                Argument will be: 'PWFAIL <UserName>'

RELOGON     : - Will be started if a user has been logged off to relogin
                right before starting the logoff batches and after user data
                back writings.

RELOGON<x>  : - The same as 'RELOGON'.

S           : - Replaces on logon the user status display just before comming
                into the menu prompt by a door.

STARTCHAT   : - If a door is found it will be used instead of the internal
                sysop chat.

                Note: If a door replaces the internal sysop chat the SYSCMDs
                      CHATIN<x> and CHATOUT<x> won't be started.
                      The door started with STARTCHAT has to call them!

SYSPW       : - Replaces the system password procedure if a system password
                is needed to login.

SYSPWFAIL   : - Will be started if the user fails entering the system
                password.

TAKEOVER    : - Do not use it!

ULSTAT      : - Calls a door after completed upload procedure with an
                argument string full of information:

                'ULSTAT FILES=%ld BYTES=%ld CPS=%lu EFF=%ld HOLDS=%ld'...
                ...' HOLDBYTES=%ld MODE=%ld INT=%ld DEL=%ld' (continued
                string)

                %ld means a long value.
                %lu means a unsigned long value.
                EFF means efficiency.
                MODE see: FAMEDefine.h "UL/DLSTAT Mode defines"
                INT means 1 for Internal or local / 0 for remote or serial.
                DEL means deleted files from upload.

ULSTAT<x>   : - The same as 'ULSTAT', but for more different doors.


@{b}@{u}Installation of Doors@{ub}@{uu}

   @{"    Door Installation    " link "DoorInstall"} - How to install Doors.

@endnode

