@REM==============================================================================

@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

                          @{b}Introduction into FAME
                         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

FAME, short for Final Amiga Mailbox Engine is a powerful MailBox Engine 
for the Amiga, a perfect plattform for multi node modeming.

FAME development began in the middle of 1993.

The reason was because of all the disadvantages of all the other
MailBox Systems available.

If you are working with FAME you will feel that FAME is something special;
it's not like other systems.

FAME is very userfriendly, and it includes brings everything you might wish;
if not we will implement it.  "Nothing is impossible" is one of our rules.

With FAME we try to follow all style guide rules.  This is also a rule for
our own developing - stuff like includes and Autodocs which will be done in
the defined rules, and not as a self-defined and confusing rule.  All that
FAME brings for development and implementation of tools and features will be
defined too.  We will give you defined style guides for developing for FAME
and if you work with them we will help you in any case.  It is important to
follow style guides to reduce errors and keep the life easy for those people
who are not programmers.

FAME has been developed to be fast and powerful with many nice features which
are as easy to handle as possible.  Just by installing FAME, you will see
that FAME does the most for you itself.

The Amiga Installer installs everything you need into the right places and
upon installation, you can do your first configurations.

On installation the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} will be started.
On the first load of the @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} it creates all the
required directories FAME needs for one node and one conference.  All data
files will be created as default ones.  After installation, you can then
start @{"Server" link "InternModules"} to take a first look.

FAME brings you, the SysOp, and your users many features - many small and
powerful ones which makes life much easier.

Developers will get much help and they can use the really fast and powerful
FAME.library containing many very interesting functions which are not only
for FAME tool developing but also very helpful for many other tools.

The FAME.library gives programmers many nice functions like pool functions to
use pools under OS2.x and many more.

The @{"Server" link "InternModules"} controls every aspect of your BBS and brings much help and
information sources like a ToolPort and the FAMESemaphore with a list for all
nodes full of information to be quickly accessed.  With the @{"SystemEditor"
link "InternModules"} you can easily set all your personal settings and you
can activate them (in later versions) at the time the BBS runs.

This is only a small introduction into what FAME does. Take a look!
And you won't turn back.

FAME will be expanded to do all the things expected of a good mailbox and
will be growing fast to become really the famous BBS on the Amiga.  I think
FAME is the 'term' under the MailBox systems.

The whole BBS is completely hardware-dependant, meaning that the only limit
FAME has is your computer equipment!

@endnode

@REM==============================================================================

@node "About" "About FAME"

                  @{b}About FAME - Final Amiga Mailbox Engine
                 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}

               A fast and mighty Mailbox system for every wishes.

FAME developing began in summer 1992 and it took over half a year to set up
all definitions. The @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} was the first executable finished in its
early but usable state.

The @{"SystemEditor" link "InternModules"} handles all the settings needed by FAME BBS to set your
system up exactly how you want to.

The @{"Server" link "InternModules"} is the heart of the System and the main controlling point.
The @{"Server" link "InternModules"} is irreplaceable, and FAME can't run without it.

@{"MainPart" link "InternModules"} is the main part of every single node and holds the most functions
to handle all special functions. If you like, it's the personal assistant of
every single user logged to any node whereas the @{"Server" link "InternModules"} is controlling the
cooperation of the 'assistants' among each another.

The @{"UserEditor" link "InternModules"} can be used to edit, validate and add user accounts to the
FAME BBS. @{"UserEditor" link "InternModules"} is an external userdata editor.
@{"UserEditor" link "InternModules"} uses MUI and is programmed by @{"Sascha Pfalz" link "SaschaPfalz"}

FAME also brings many different other Modules for bulletins, doors and system
handling like CoProcesses.
Examples are @{"FAMEHydra" link "FAMEHydra.guide/Main"}, FAMEChat, FAMEFullEd (emacs like fullscreen editor),
FAMEFileCehcker (background check, file id and posting) and many more.


                  @{i}FAME is developed with the following tools:@{ui}

                                 SAS/C v6.56

                              GadToolsBox v2.0b

                            Directory Opus v4.12A+

@endnode

